256,5,H1 DetChar - O4a lines statistics and most problematic artifacts,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79579,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Fri, 16 Aug 2024 16:00:32 -0700","Evan Goetz, Alan Knee, Ansel Neunzert (on behalf of line list contributors, see LIGO-T2400204 ) Summary: Version 1 of the lines and combs list of non-astrophysical artifacts yields insights into the O4a H1 data about long duration narrow spectral artifacts. In summary, H1 data has nearly 7x more of these artifacts than L1, mostly due to the much higher proliferation of comb artifacts. H1 data also suffers from a large number of narrow artifacts in the ~100 Hz bands near test mass violin resonance harmonics, usually during times of rung up violin resonances. Without careful handling of the data in frequency bands near the violin modes, nearly 18% of the 10 Hz - 2 kHz band is contaminated, though more careful handling results in about 6% of the band being contaminated (roughly equivalent to L1). The L1 detector does not suffer from these same artifacts. Details: After compiling a list of vetted, non-astrophysical artifacts into the version 1 lines and combs list for O4a, we extracted some statistics for each detector in order to compare and contrast the data quality from this perspective, and to determine which of the artifacts are most problematic for long duration narrowband searches (CW or narrowband directed stochastic searches).New for this observing run, we have two new features for the lines list: 1) artifacts with known time variation (turn on/turn off) where we can establish reasonable metrics for their presence in the data we also provide a segment list for times those artifacts are present; 2) a new type 3 artifact that is not simply a narrow frequency band for a single artifact, but rather a band (typically 1 Hz or larger) with many narrow artifacts degrading the data quality within the band. Type H1 L1-----------------------------------------Total number of artifacts 1721 251Number of vetted combs 26 16Comb lines 1510 168Type 3 artifacts 29 0Vetoed band percentage(excl. type 3 artifacts) 5.8% 6.3%Vetoed band percentage(incl. type 3 artifacts) 17.9% 6.3% Most problematic H1 artifacts:1) Type 3 artifacts: non-stationary line artifacts impacting ~100 Hz bands around TM violin resonances - partial understanding of some of these artifacts due to calibration line mixing with violin resonances (future aLOG), but not all artifacts are understood2) 9.5 Hz comb triplet: comb of line triplets present from 10 Hz to 2000 Hz (seen weakly at L1) - potential cause identified in PSL flow sensors ( LHO aLOG 79533 )3) ~11.11 Hz comb seen in both H1 and L1 - not understood. It was also seen at H1 in O3.4) ~11.9 Hz comb seen in both H1 and L1 - not understood. See also checks on different changes . Seen also in O3 H1 data.H1 artifacts that have been mitigated:1) Hartmann wavefront sensor (HWS) comb mitigated near 1 Hz , near 5 Hz , and near 7 Hz combs2) OM2 heater driver comb mitigated ~1.66 Hz comb (also 1.1086 Hz briefly appearing)Ongoing detailed analysis (future aLOG) of the violin mode region contamination indicates that at least some of the lines are calibration line + violin mode mixing. We are not yet sure whether this explains all the contaminated time periods in O4a, nor to all the contaminated lines, and we have not done a systematic comparison with L1. However, at the overview level, the mixing of calibration lines and violin resonances seems much worse in H1 than in L1. Perhaps this is somehow related to the new signal readout chain installed ahead of O4 that is different from the readout at L1. The number of lines also should instill some caution into further efforts to put additional calibration monitoring lines into the DARM control loop as the added lines would greatly increase the number of artifacts in the spectrum. This needs to be solved before further lines are added. We anticipate further understanding of the O4a data with continued investigation, so the number of artifacts known to be non-astrophysical may go up.CAL, DetChar, ISC","{'term': 'H1 DetChar', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: evan.goetz@ligo.org

Report ID: 79579

Evan Goetz, Alan Knee, Ansel Neunzert (on behalf of line list contributors, see LIGO-T2400204)

Version 1 of the lines and combs list of non-astrophysical artifacts yields insights into the O4a H1 data about long duration narrow spectral artifacts. In summary, H1 data has nearly 7x more of these artifacts than L1, mostly due to the much higher proliferation of comb artifacts. H1 data also suffers from a large number of narrow artifacts in the ~100 Hz bands near test mass violin resonance harmonics, usually during times of rung up violin resonances. Without careful handling of the data in frequency bands near the violin modes, nearly 18% of the 10 Hz - 2 kHz band is contaminated, though more careful handling results in about 6% of the band being contaminated (roughly equivalent to L1). The L1 detector does not suffer from these same artifacts.

After compiling a list of vetted, non-astrophysical artifacts into the version 1 lines and combs list for O4a, we extracted some statistics for each detector in order to compare and contrast the data quality from this perspective, and to determine which of the artifacts are most problematic for long duration narrowband searches (CW or narrowband directed stochastic searches).

New for this observing run, we have two new features for the lines list: 1) artifacts with known time variation (turn on/turn off) where we can establish reasonable metrics for their presence in the data we also provide a segment list for times those artifacts are present; 2) a new type 3 artifact that is not simply a narrow frequency band for a single artifact, but rather a band (typically 1 Hz or larger) with many narrow artifacts degrading the data quality within the band.

1) Type 3 artifacts: non-stationary line artifacts impacting ~100 Hz bands around TM violin resonances - partial understanding of some of these artifacts due to calibration line mixing with violin resonances (future aLOG), but not all artifacts are understood
2) 9.5 Hz comb triplet: comb of line triplets present from 10 Hz to 2000 Hz (seen weakly at L1) - potential cause identified in PSL flow sensors (LHO aLOG 79533)
3) ~11.11 Hz comb seen in both H1 and L1 - not understood. It was also seen at H1 in O3.
4) ~11.9 Hz comb seen in both H1 and L1 - not understood. See also checks on different changes. Seen also in O3 H1 data.
H1 artifacts that have been mitigated:
1) Hartmann wavefront sensor (HWS) comb mitigated near 1 Hz, near 5 Hz, and near 7 Hz combs
2) OM2 heater driver comb mitigated ~1.66 Hz comb (also 1.1086 Hz briefly appearing)

Ongoing detailed analysis (future aLOG) of the violin mode region contamination indicates that at least some of the lines are calibration line + violin mode mixing. We are not yet sure whether this explains all the contaminated time periods in O4a, nor to all the contaminated lines, and we have not done a systematic comparison with L1. However, at the overview level, the mixing of calibration lines and violin resonances seems much worse in H1 than in L1. Perhaps this is somehow related to the new signal readout chain installed ahead of O4 that is different from the readout at L1. The number of lines also should instill some caution into further efforts to put additional calibration monitoring lines into the DARM control loop as the added lines would greatly increase the number of artifacts in the spectrum. This needs to be solved before further lines are added.
We anticipate further understanding of the O4a data with continued investigation, so the number of artifacts known to be non-astrophysical may go up.

Author: janos.csizmazia@ligo.org

Report ID: 79577

Late entry from yesterday:

- The controllers of IP1, IP2, IP3, and IP14 ion pumps were replaced with the old rebuilt Varian controllers, in order to prepare for valving the ion pumps in (IP4 still has its original Varian controller). This is the reason why these Ion pumps turned red in the vacuum MEDM screen
- The new instrument air scroll compressor came online: it was valved in, and the Kobelco was valved out. Huge kudos for Tyler and Eric and the FAC team!

- The large Ion pumps were valved in. At first IP1 and IP2 - these pumps have Chevron baffles, so the immediate gas rush was somewhat mitigated by valving these 2 in first. Then IP3 and IP4. Then, after a few hours IP14 (HAM6)
- The pressure immediately went down from 3.7E-7 to 1.7E-7, and it is dropping. The ion current in the IPs has not started to go down just yet
As soon as the pressure according to PT-120 reaches 8E-8 Torr, the gate valves will be opened. HAM7 and the filter cavity will follow after a few hours.
Huge congratulations to Gerardo and Travis, and everyone who helped the vacuum team to achieve this fast pumpdown, and that the plan of opening up on Monday (19th) is still on.

To check that we can get light through to HAM6, we brought the IFO to the same alignment as in alog79193, where they also had HAM5,6 HEPI locked. We started with the fast shutter closed. With alignments the same we went into a single bounce configuration with ITMY aligned and went up to 10W. With AS_C centered, H1:ASC-AS_C_SUM_OUTPUT was at 0.0078 vs the 0.0045 reported on July 17 reported in the linked alog above (73% increase). We ran into some P motion when we turned sensor correction on, but maybe this is expected while we have some HEPIs locked. The AS Air camera had the slightest bit of a spot on the top left corner of it when we were centered.

260,9,H1 DetChar - SQZ ADF line moved from 322 Hz to 10 kHz,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79573,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Fri, 16 Aug 2024 12:14:30 -0700","Alan Knee, Camilla Compton, Evan Goetz We changed the SQZ ADF frequency from 322 Hz to 10 kHz where it should not impact long duration searches ( figure ), using the command 'python /opt/rtcds/userapps/release/sqz/h1/scripts/ADF/setADF.py -f 10000'. This line appeared in DARM during O4a when it was set to 1300 Hz. It was moved from 1300 Hz to 322 Hz around 1397588061 (2024/04/19 18:54:03 UTC, figure ), and was visible in Fscan spectra in O4b ( figure ). This line was previously turned ""off"" on 2024/04/04 (see 76962 ), but was still visible in DARM (at reduced amplitude) due to the RF driver being left on. You can see the change in behaviour in the attached line height plots. The first shows the height of the 1300 Hz line during April 2024, where the line is at first ""on"", decreases in strength after April 4, and then disappears on April 19 when it was moved to 322 Hz. Author: alan.knee@ligo.org

Report ID: 79573

Alan Knee, Camilla Compton, Evan Goetz

We changed the SQZ ADF frequency from 322 Hz to 10 kHz where it should not impact long duration searches (figure), using the command 'python /opt/rtcds/userapps/release/sqz/h1/scripts/ADF/setADF.py -f 10000'. This line appeared in DARM during O4a when it was set to 1300 Hz. It was moved from 1300 Hz to 322 Hz around 1397588061 (2024/04/19 18:54:03 UTC, figure), and was visible in Fscan spectra in O4b (figure).

This line was previously turned "off" on 2024/04/04 (see 76962), but was still visible in DARM (at reduced amplitude) due to the RF driver being left on. You can see the change in behaviour in the attached line height plots. The first shows the height of the 1300 Hz line during April 2024, where the line is at first "on", decreases in strength after April 4, and then disappears on April 19 when it was moved to 322 Hz. The second shows the height at 322 Hz, which appears on April 19.

275,24,H1 ISC - Looking for correlations between the OFI Incident(TM) and earthquakes,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79548,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Thu, 15 Aug 2024 16:24:36 -0700","We were exploring any weird behavior during the locklosses preceding the OFI burns to try and narrow down possible causes, and we recently learned from a scientist experienced with KTP optics that the movement of a high powered beam passing through the KTP could cause damage to the optic, so that created the theory that this could have happened due to earthquakes. There were a couple of decently-sized earthquakes before the incidents: April Incident ( seismic/LL summary alog79132 ) - April 18th - nearby earthquake from Canada - we lost lock from this ( lockloss ndscope ) - April 20th - nearby earthquake from Richland - stayed locked - April 23rd - drop in output power noticed - the lockloss right before this had NOT been caused by an earthquake ( previous lockloss ndscope ) July Incident - July 11th - nearby earthquake from Canada ( alog79023 ) ( lockloss ndscope , zoomed out lockloss ndscope ) - July 12th - noticed similarities to the April incident We used ndscope to compare ground motion to DARM, AS_A, AS_C, and the IFO state. So yes, we did have two decently sized earthquakes (+a local one) before the IFO burns took place, but we also have earthquakes hitting us all the time, many with higher ground velocities. Overall, we did not see anything strange during these earthquake locklosses in the AS_A and AS_C channels that would lead us to think that the earthquakes played a part in the OFI issues. DetChar ","{'term': 'H1 ISC', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: oli.patane@ligo.org

Report ID: 79548

We were exploring any weird behavior during the locklosses preceding the OFI burns to try and narrow down possible causes, and we recently learned from a scientist experienced with KTP optics that the movement of a high powered beam passing through the KTP could cause damage to the optic, so that created the theory that this could have happened due to earthquakes.
There were a couple of decently-sized earthquakes before the incidents:
- April 18th - nearby earthquake from Canada - we lost lock from this (lockloss ndscope)
- April 20th - nearby earthquake from Richland - stayed locked
- April 23rd - drop in output power noticed - the lockloss right before this had NOT been caused by an earthquake (previous lockloss ndscope)
- July 11th - nearby earthquake from Canada (alog79023) (lockloss ndscope, zoomed out lockloss ndscope)
- July 12th - noticed similarities to the April incident

We used ndscope to compare ground motion to DARM, AS_A, AS_C, and the IFO state. In looking over the ndscopes, we don't see anything that would make us think that these earthquakes changed anything in the output arm.

So yes, we did have two decently sized earthquakes (+a local one) before the IFO burns took place, but we also have earthquakes hitting us all the time, many with higher ground velocities. Overall, we did not see anything strange during these earthquake locklosses in the AS_A and AS_C channels that would lead us to think that the earthquakes played a part in the OFI issues.

277,26,H1 DetChar - Comment to Issue with calibration line subtraction at beginning of locks,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79558,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Thu, 15 Aug 2024 14:56:32 -0700","A while back, I investigated this and found that the reason for occasional early lock subtraction problems is that, at the end of the previous lock, the lines were turned off, but the TFs were still being calculated. Then, at the beginning of the next lock, it takes several minutes (due to the 512-s running median) to update the TFs with accurate values. There were two problems that contributed to this issue. I added some more gating in the pipeline to use the line amplitude channels to gate the TF calculation. This fix was included included in gstlal-calibration-1.5.3 , as well as the version currently in production (1.5.4). However, there have been some instances in which those channels were indicating that the lines were on when they were actually off at the end of the previous lock, which means this code change, by itself, does not fix the problem in all cases. The version that is currently in testing, gstlal-calibration-1.5.7 , includes some other fixes for line subtraction, which may or may not improve this problem. A more reliable way to solve this issue would be to ensure that the line amplitude channels we are using always carry accurate real-time information. Specifically, we would need to prevent the occurance of the lines turning off long before these channels indicate this has occurred. The names of these channels are: {IFO}:SUS-ETMX_L{1,2,3}_CAL_LINE_CLKGAIN {IFO}:CAL-PCAL{X,Y}_PCALOSC{1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9}_OSC_SINGAIN CAL","{'term': 'H1 DetChar', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: aaron.viets@ligo.org

Report ID: 79558

A while back, I investigated this and found that the reason for occasional early lock subtraction problems is that, at the end of the previous lock, the lines were turned off, but the TFs were still being calculated.  Then, at the beginning of the next lock, it takes several minutes (due to the 512-s running median) to update the TFs with accurate values.  There were two problems that contributed to this issue.  I added some more gating in the pipeline to use the line amplitude channels to gate the TF calculation.  This fix was included included in gstlal-calibration-1.5.3, as well as the version currently in production (1.5.4). However, there have been some instances in which those channels were indicating that the lines were on when they were actually off at the end of the previous lock, which means this code change, by itself, does not fix the problem in all cases.  The version that is currently in testing, gstlal-calibration-1.5.7, includes some other fixes for line subtraction, which may or may not improve this problem.

A more reliable way to solve this issue would be to ensure that the line amplitude channels we are using always carry accurate real-time information.  Specifically, we would need to prevent the occurance of the lines turning off long before these channels indicate this has occurred.  The names of these channels are:

Author: genevieve.connolly@ligo.org

Report ID: 79546

Yesterday Sam and I went around the LVEA with a portable accelerometer (H1:PEM-CS_ADC_5_28_2K_OUT_DQ) to investigate a ~35.4 Hz peak. This peak dates back to at least June 2023, possibly longer. We placed the portable accelerometer in seven different spots, each time against a wall except for one spot near BS1. See the attachment 1 for the reference map. The peak appears strongest at REF0 and REF5 as seen in attachment 2. We attempted to test outside near the Mitsubishis (outside the OSB kitchen) and the southeast-facing mechanical room wall as well but had data retrieval issues, so we'll go back to that soon.

We are also investigating the ~36 Hz peak seen in attachment 2, strongest near the X OL. It seems to have been around since at least 2023-05-08, but more investigation is needed to find out when it started and if it shows up consistently every day. The frequency of this peak oscillates on a range of about 1 Hz. Attachment 3 shows the peak in H1:PEM-CS_LVEAFLOOR_XCRYO_Z_DQ and H1:GDS-CALIB_STRAIN_CLEAN. This peak also travels between 30-40 Hz, generally near 40 Hz at the beginning and end of the UTC day and dropping towards 30 Hz in the middle of the day, as seen in attachment 4 from the summary pages.

Author: david.barker@ligo.org

Report ID: 79544

WP12035
Yesterday thermocouple B (TC-B) failed during the fill. Its wire broke and its temperature railed at +1372C. The fill proceded with TC-A to completion.
If TC-A had similarly failed, the fill would have continued until either the discharge line pressure exceeded its trip pressure; or the fill timed out after 30 minutes.
Today's code modification adds a check when reading the TCs that they are not greater than the nominal_max temps (+40C).
Providing at least one TC is in operational range the fill will continue, but now if no TCs are operational the fill will abort with an error.
The new code was installed at 9am today, it will run for the first time during Thursday's fill.

During this investigation I noted that the discharge_line_pressure trip is 2.0PSI. Operationally this pressure has never exceeded 0.6PSI so I lowered the trip down to 1.0PSI.

",79544,david.barker@ligo.org

Joe B, Matt

We lost lock at 5:01 UTC due to what looks like a strong wind period. We have an issue with the IFO relocking with an issue with the calibration lines turning on and it not being able to find a channel (due to it being mis-spelt). Im currently not finding where the missing channel lives as my CTRL F search for that channel name is not being successful (Im sure it must be in ICSLOCK.py somewhere, but its coming up as no results.....I will keep searching).  This is the first time we are relocking since we swapped from Pcal Y to Pcal x due to an issue with Pcal y. Ive sent a message to Vlad and Joe B to see if they can help me work through the issue.
I have us in corrective maintenance while search for it.

UPDATE: Joe B (big thanks to Joe for responding after being woken up so early in the morning) found where it lived in ISC_Lock.py (im not sure why my search for the name was unsuccessful.....), corrected the issue and were able to reach low noise. Author: joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org

Report ID: 72724

[Matt H, Brian O., TJ, Vlad B, Joe B]

So it looks like about 2 hours ago, around 2:09 UTC, the PCALY power went down, and then went highly variable.  I'm not sure if this AOM or insufficient laser power, although I tend to the think the later.  We will run on PCALX until we get the opportunity to address this, most likely Monday.
So we did the following emergency changes to make that PCALX change happen:
1) Flipped the l1calcs model reference from EY RX PD to EX RX PD
3) Turned off all the excitations on the EY photon calibrator
5) Turned off the monitoring lines on the EX photon calibrator
6) Moved the 16.9 Hz, 434.9 Hz and 1083.1 Hz the EX photon calibrator
7) Modified the ISC_LOCK guardian to turn those lines on only on EX
8) Modified the nominal and request states of the HIGH_FREQ_LINES guardian to IDLE
9) Modified IFO_CALIB guardian to not run in the IDLE state
10) Added a -1 to the gain in the EX RX PD readback.
We looked at the L1:GDS-CALIB_STRAIN and L1:GDS-CALIB_STRAIN_CLEAN to confirm they looked reasonable. Also spot checked the GDS kappa generation to make sure they had the correct sign.CAL

Author: joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org

Report ID: 72713

I have modified the ISC_LOCK guardian LOW_NOISE state for the weekend so that if we lose lock, we should hit reload on ISC_LOCK guardian.

The changes will correct the OAF-CAL_DARM spectrum on the wall (while being transparent to the main calibration pipeline) once we reach the LOW_NOISE state.  It'll use 1.05 as the current kappa_c values and 1.02 for the current kappa_tst value.  I'll fix this on Monday once we figure out what power and time dependent correction factors we have going forward, or we'll push a new calibration to make it a non-issue.CAL",72713,joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org

326,75,L1 TCS - Comment to End of Shift Summary,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72706,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Fri, 16 Aug 2024 18:03:18 -0500","Brian O, Anamaira, Michael L, Karla, Gary, Matt A meeting was had between various parties about what we do regarding the TCS CO2Y (well both CO2 systems) laser for the immediate future (because if the TCS CO2 laser was to trip off when no one is here, then we would lose lock eventually and we dont know when we will get back to observing). One of the issues is that we are kind of blind to the cause of the issue at the moment. Not a lot is really trended in terms of the faults that can happen. Another issue is that the viewport IR sensor and laser temperature sensor share an alarm channel (for historical reasons, due to one being added at the last minute) . A third issue is that the faults arent latched so if the issue goes away before we can see it on the controller, we dont know the cause of the issue. Thus for this weekend the decision was made to run at lower input power (~56.5W) and run with no CO2 this weekend and try to set up some monitoring on some of the channels next week to see if it can help us track down what might be the issue. While trying to go to lower input power we lost lock, and so we took the opportunity to add some monitoring to the IR sensor. The box in question we are going to run some temporary monitoring to is D1300249-V3 (version 4 isnt actually in existence). We are adding a breakoff board and going to pickoff to the VIn point and ""borrowed"" a PEM channel to monitor what happens to the IR sensor channel. The attached picture shows how we plan to hook up the signal pickoff to the box. We have the signal trending in L1:PEM-CS_ADC_4_21_OUT_DQ (the calibration of this channel is 4V/2^16cts). This signal read zero before we connected it and then went to a negative voltage (which we dont understand why). We had the laser on for a very short time and then caught it turning OFF. In the second attachment the top plot is the temporary monitoring of the IR sensor we just setup, the second plot is looking at the output of the laser, the third plot is looking at the RTD and IR sensor interlock signal and he bottom trace is the RTD/temperature of the laser. We really arent sure what to make of what we see as the ""glitch"" in the IR sensor happens 1 second after the laser went off. And the temperature of the laser would go down when the laser is off (and I see no glitch which would turn the laser off). So really not sure at the moment what this tells us, but its another data point for us to consider.... The CO2Y laser is still OFF as Karla and Michael are doing some experiments with the power supply as they are seeing something in relation to that. OpsInfo, TCS ","{'term': 'L1 TCS', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: matthew.heintze@ligo.org

Report ID: 72706

Brian O, Anamaira, Michael L, Karla, Gary, Matt

A meeting was had between various parties about what we do regarding the TCS CO2Y (well both CO2 systems) laser for the immediate future (because if the TCS CO2 laser was to trip off when no one is here, then we would lose lock eventually and we dont know when we will get back to observing).

One of the issues is that we are kind of blind to the cause of the issue at the moment. Not a lot is really trended in terms of the faults that can happen. Another issue is that the viewport IR sensor and laser temperature sensor share an alarm channel (for historical reasons, due to one being added at the last minute). A third issue is that the faults arent latched so if the issue goes away before we can see it on the controller, we dont know the cause of the issue. Thus for this weekend the decision was made to run at lower input power (~56.5W) and run with no CO2 this weekend and try to set up some monitoring on some of the channels next week to see if it can help us track down what might be the issue. While trying to go to lower input power we lost lock, and so we took the opportunity to add some monitoring to the IR sensor.

The box in question we are going to run some temporary monitoring to is D1300249-V3 (version 4 isnt actually in existence). We are adding a breakoff board and going to pickoff to the VIn point and "borrowed" a PEM channel to monitor what happens to the IR sensor channel. The attached picture shows how we plan to hook up the signal pickoff to the box.

We have the signal trending in L1:PEM-CS_ADC_4_21_OUT_DQ (the calibration of this channel is 4V/2^16cts). This signal read zero before we connected it and then went to a negative voltage (which we dont understand why). We had the laser on for a very short time and then caught it turning OFF. In the second attachment the top plot is the temporary monitoring of the IR sensor we just setup, the second plot is looking at the output of the laser, the third plot is looking at the RTD and IR sensor interlock signal and he bottom trace is the RTD/temperature of the laser. We really arent sure what to make of what we see as the "glitch" in the IR sensor happens 1 second after the laser went off. And the temperature of the laser would go down when the laser is off (and I see no glitch which would turn the laser off).
So really not sure at the moment what this tells us, but its another data point for us to consider....
The CO2Y laser is still OFF as Karla and Michael are doing some experiments with the power supply as they are seeing something in relation to that.

Author: evan.goetz@ligo.org

Report ID: 72705

Evan Goetz, Alan Knee, Ansel Neunzert (on behalf of line list contributors, see LIGO-T2400204)

Version 1 of the lines and combs list of non-astrophysical artifacts yields insights into the O4a L1 data about long duration narrow spectral artifacts. In summary, H1 data has nearly 7x more of these artifacts than L1, mostly due to the much higher proliferation of comb artifacts. H1 data also suffers from a large number of narrow artifacts in the ~100 Hz bands near test mass violin resonance harmonics, usually during times of rung up violin resonances. Without careful handling of this data, nearly 18% of the 10 Hz - 2 kHz band is contaminated, though more careful handling results in about 6% of the band being contaminated (roughly equivalent to L1). The L1 detector does not suffer from these same artifacts.

After compiling a list of vetted, non-astrophysical artifacts into the version 1 lines and combs list for O4a, we extracted some statistics for each detector in order to compare and contrast the data quality from this perspective, and to determine which of the artifacts are most problematic for long duration narrowband searches (CW or narrowband directed stochastic searches).

New for this observing run, we have two new features for the lines list: 1) artifacts with known time variation (turn on/turn off) where we can establish reasonable metrics for their presence in the data we also provide a segment list for times those artifacts are present; 2) a new type 3 artifact that is not simply a narrow frequency band for a single artifact, but rather a band (typically 1 Hz or larger) with many narrow artifacts degrading the data quality within the band.
1) ~11.11 Hz comb seen in both H1 and L1 - not understood. Seen also in O3 at H1 but not L1
2) ~11.9 Hz comb seen in both H1 and L1 - not understood. See also checks on different changes. Seen also in O3 at H1 but not L1
3) 9.5 Hz comb triplet: weak comb of line triplets present from 10 Hz to 80 Hz (seen strongly at H1) - potentially the same cause as at LHO related to the PSL flow meter sensors (LHO aLOG 79533)
4) Various 1 Hz [1] [2] and 10 Hz combs seen also in O3 in L1

We anticipate further understanding of the O4a data with continued investigation, so the number of artifacts known to be non-astrophysical may go up. We have not reported on, for example, any calibration line mixing that we know to be a problem historically.

340,89,L1 SEI - Semi-adaptive control test (very preliminary),https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72689,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Fri, 16 Aug 2024 00:00:49 -0500","Huyen, Terrence 2024-08-13 WP #11682 Previous work: SEI 2471 , SEI 2430 . I am posting my work here on LLO logbook as requested. This is only a (very) preliminary test of the semi-adaptive control framework that I have been developing. No configurations were changed. No systems were affected. The goal was to test a few things: 1) Basic functionality of my the framework, Seibot , programmed in Python, 2) New sensor correction and complementary filters (blends) that offer comparable low- and high-frequency performances to the ones in use, 3) Just to test and see what challenges we might face in the future. We emphasize that this is only a functionality test and not a performance test . Seibot currently supports Python and command line usages, which are not the easiest to use. Later we will be added 2 modes of usages, 1) GUI showing predicted motion with selected filters, allowing users to see effects of different filters in real time, and 2) guardian that achieve the an autonomous version of semi-adaptive control. Seibot does the following, as described in the documentation: 1) reads user configuration files, foton files, model parameters, and sensor readouts via CDSutils, 2) compile necessary data and filters to construct a simulated isolation system, 3) simulate all possible outcomes with all possible filter configurations, and finally 4) evaluate these outcomes and select a set of filters that is the best. We have generated 9 sets of sensor correction filters and 9 sets of complementary filters for the test, which are optimized for the 9 scenarios consisting of 3 levels of seismic noises and 3 levels of ground/platform tilt, using the H-infinity method . Combined with the filters in use, this gives 10*10 = 100 different seismic control configurations that populate the parameter space that we can seek optimization on. Figure 5 and Figure 6 show the magnitude responses of these filters, which are already installed in Foton. These filters have better low- and high-frequency responses compared to what was shown in SEI 2430 . Previous ones were barely functional due to low-frequency noises, and inject ~10x noises at 10 Hz. We ran the test two times, without and with seismic injection, each time we took a measurement of the HAM8-ISI motion with the filters originally in use, and with the filters suggested by Seibot. Criterion being used here is the minimum displacement RMS. Yes, we know this is not the best criterion but we use this anyway for testing's sake The filters were switched on-the-fly with the faders to ensure its functionality. Figure 1 and Figure 2 show the predictions and selections of HAM8 table motion made by Seibot, without and with injection, respectively. Figure 3 and Figure 4 show the measured HAM8 motions, without and with injection, respectively. The actual table motion is, roughly speaking, the minimum between the CPS and the T240 signal. Without injection, the secondary microseism is very low. In this case, the table motion is RMS dominated by the inertial noise. Therefore, Seibot prioritized low-frequency noise suppression, as indicated by the lower CPS signal in Figure 3 below 0.1 Hz, which makes seismic noise suppression above .1 Hz worse as they're not RMS dominated. With the seismic noise injection, the secondary microseism is very high and becomes relevant in RMS. This spectrum was taken from December where we experienced lock loss. As shown in Figure 4 , the filters chosen by Seibot offers better suppression everywhere, except around 1 Hz, which preliminarily proves the functionality of Seibot. We encountered a few challenges during the tests, one being tilt-horizontal coupling noise in the GS13 on the table. Since Seibot takes a 1-hr long time series in the past for estimating sensor and seismic noises dynamically, any tilt transient/gitches present within the hour would render the GS13 spectrum useless, making further prediction impossible. I don't have any good ideas how to get around this. Maybe I will have some after my long vacation. SEI, SEI HAM ISI ","{'term': 'L1 SEI', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: terrence.tsang@ligo.org

Report ID: 72689

Huyen, Terrence
Previous work: SEI 2471, SEI 2430. I am posting my work here on LLO logbook as requested.
This is only a (very) preliminary test of the semi-adaptive control framework that I have been developing. No configurations were changed. No systems were affected.

The goal was to test a few things: 1) Basic functionality of my the framework, Seibot, programmed in Python, 2) New sensor correction and complementary filters (blends) that offer comparable low- and high-frequency performances to the ones in use, 3) Just to test and see what challenges we might face in the future.
We emphasize that this is only a functionality test and not a performance test.
Seibot currently supports Python and command line usages, which are not the easiest to use.

Later we will be added 2 modes of usages, 1) GUI showing predicted motion with selected filters, allowing users to see effects of different filters in real time, and 2) guardian that achieve the an autonomous version of semi-adaptive control.

Seibot does the following, as described in the documentation: 1) reads user configuration files, foton files, model parameters, and sensor readouts via CDSutils, 2) compile necessary data and filters to construct a simulated isolation system, 3) simulate all possible outcomes with all possible filter configurations, and finally 4) evaluate these outcomes and select a set of filters that is the best.

We have generated 9 sets of sensor correction filters and 9 sets of complementary filters for the test, which are optimized for the 9 scenarios consisting of 3 levels of seismic noises and 3 levels of ground/platform tilt, using the H-infinity method.
Combined with the filters in use, this gives 10*10 = 100 different seismic control configurations that populate the parameter space that we can seek optimization on.
Figure 5 and Figure 6 show the magnitude responses of these filters, which are already installed in Foton.
These filters have better low- and high-frequency responses compared to what was shown in SEI 2430. Previous ones were barely functional due to low-frequency noises, and inject ~10x noises at 10 Hz.
We ran the test two times, without and with seismic injection, each time we took a measurement of the HAM8-ISI motion with the filters originally in use, and with the filters suggested by Seibot.
Criterion being used here is the minimum displacement RMS. Yes, we know this is not the best criterion but we use this anyway for testing's sake
The filters were switched on-the-fly with the faders to ensure its functionality.
Figure 1 and Figure 2 show the predictions and selections of HAM8 table motion made by Seibot, without and with injection, respectively.
Figure 3 and Figure 4 show the measured HAM8 motions, without and with injection, respectively.
The actual table motion is, roughly speaking, the minimum between the CPS and the T240 signal.
Without injection, the secondary microseism is very low.
In this case, the table motion is RMS dominated by the inertial noise.

Therefore, Seibot prioritized low-frequency noise suppression, as indicated by the lower CPS signal in Figure 3 below 0.1 Hz, which makes seismic noise suppression above .1 Hz worse as they're not RMS dominated.
With the seismic noise injection, the secondary microseism is very high and becomes relevant in RMS. This spectrum was taken from December where we experienced lock loss.
As shown in Figure 4, the filters chosen by Seibot offers better suppression everywhere, except around 1 Hz, which preliminarily proves the functionality of Seibot.
We encountered a few challenges during the tests, one being tilt-horizontal coupling noise in the GS13 on the table.

Since Seibot takes a 1-hr long time series in the past for estimating sensor and seismic noises dynamically, any tilt transient/gitches present within the hour would render the GS13 spectrum useless, making further prediction impossible.
I don't have any good ideas how to get around this. Maybe I will have some after my long vacation.

Author: joe.hanson@ligo.org

Report ID: 72691

8/15/24 J Hanson
2100 Observing, were commissioning about 2 hrs ago
2135 Austin called, most likely due to the power outage
2147 TJ is turning off the SEI AI chassis
2155 Huyen to Ham Shack to turn off AI chassis
2226 I am back from the Ends to turn on Hepi
2231 Josh and Huyen turning on the AI chassis
2234 Adam putting all Sus in Aligned
2240 Anamaria restarted models for ITM’s & BS
2242 Karla turned on the TCS lasers
2254 Adam restarting the Laser again as per Matt, (some order condition)
2313 Mike and Doug restarting the Beckhoff chassis
2357 Stopped at 10 watts to Damp ITMX Violin Modes
0007 Waiting on the R-wave from a 6.1 Quake in Taiwan
0010 Still have weather moving through the Area
0050 Lock loss tool is dead frs 31852
0130 ALS both have pink Guardians with “User code error”
0132 Quake is allowing locking now, but for ALS
0139 ALS finally reloaded after Init-ing a few times
0223 Broke lock, at 59 watts, one of the power bumps I think.
0316 Lots of SDF’s, Begum is here helping, Adam, and Huyen are helping remotely.
0430 Range has taken a dive from 170 to the mid 150’s in the last .5hr
0452 Turning off 2nd and 3rd order Violins took us out of Observing for SDF’s, I accepted all.

Thanks to everyone who helped get us back into Observing, great teamwork.

Report ID: 72690

The ALS XARM guardian issue looks like the same awg error that occurs when the end station sus models are restarted, although I don't think they were restarted today, so this is a little puzzling. That said, if the issue arises again, I suggest restarting the node:

column2: • Before restarting the node, note the requested state, then put the guardian in the SHUTTERED state, Although if it's in an error state, you might need to manually jump out of the state (on the guardmedm screen - click the MANUAL button, request QPDS_LOCKED, click LOAD, click the AUTO button, then request SHUTTERED).
• Restart the node by opening a terminal and the type 'guardctrl restart ALS_XARM' and press enter.
• After the node has restarted set the requested state back to what it was before (probably PDH_LOCKED).

344,93,L1 ISC - ALSX sweep test,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72687,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Thu, 15 Aug 2024 21:07:26 -0500","[Begum, Adam, Anamaria] We did a brief sweep of ALSX frequency while IFO fully locked. The sweep data is very noisy but we learned some things: Spectra measured during this attempt is attached here . The black trace is with the ALSX shuttered, while the red trace is when it is off resonance. There is no significant difference between these two spectra. The green trace is with the ALSX frequency near fundamental mode resonance but the PDH unlocked, while the purple trace is with PDH locked at the fundamental mode . The additional noise at purple is not terribly high, this is encouraging. Blue trace is near a higher order mode resonance, with the lower power levels in that mode, it shows less noise than the green trace. The ALSX frequency sweep shows large higher order mode content, although it is worth noting some of these modes were circularly symmetric ones. There is room for improvement for the alignment. Here is a brief description of the procedure: Release green photons Lock ALS green QPDs Increase ESD range by increasing bias (-100 V --> -200 V) and decrease gain (1.32 --> 0.66): Tune onto resonance using VCO Adjust alignment using the PZT offsets Lock PDH by hand: IN1, COM1, BOOST1 (no gain change) Unlock PDH, sweep frequency (0.001 V steps size, 400 seconds total time) 15/08/2024 UTC 17:13:00 ALSX shuttered UTC 17:18:00 ALSX unlocked, near higher order mode UTC 17:21:00 ALSX off-resonance UTC 17:30:00 ALSX unlocked, near fundamental mode UTC 17:50:30 ALSX locked on fundamental mode /data/begum.kabagoz/ALS/alsx_trial.xml ISC ","{'term': 'L1 ISC', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: begum.kabagoz@ligo.org

Report ID: 72687

[Begum, Adam, Anamaria]
We did a brief sweep of ALSX frequency while IFO fully locked. The sweep data is very noisy but we learned some things:

Spectra measured during this attempt is attached here. The black trace is with the ALSX shuttered, while the red trace is when it is off resonance. There is no significant difference between these two spectra. The green trace is with the ALSX frequency near fundamental mode resonance but the PDH unlocked, while the purple trace is with PDH locked at the fundamental mode. The additional noise at purple is not terribly high, this is encouraging. Blue trace is near a higher order mode resonance, with the lower power levels in that mode, it shows less noise than the green trace.
The ALSX frequency sweep shows large higher order mode content, although it is worth noting some of these modes were circularly symmetric ones. There is room for improvement for the alignment.
Here is a brief description of the procedure:

column2: • Increase ESD range by increasing bias (-100 V --> -200 V) and decrease gain (1.32 --> 0.66):
• Lock PDH by hand: IN1, COM1, BOOST1 (no gain change)
• Unlock PDH, sweep frequency (0.001 V steps size, 400 seconds total time)

column1: UTC 17:18:00     ALSX unlocked, near higher order mode
UTC 17:30:00     ALSX unlocked, near fundamental mode
UTC 17:50:30     ALSX locked on fundamental mode

358,107,L1 ISC - ITMX spot move test,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72660,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Thu, 15 Aug 2024 13:35:25 -0500","[Anamaria, Karla] Yesterday, during the commissioning period, we adjusted the position of the spot on ITMX to see how it affects optical gain and sideband buildup and map the relation between the camera and HWS. The Interferometer (IFO) has been consistently operating at 72W input power. The images from the HWS sensor at ITMX show the presence of a ""point absorber."" In the image ITMX_PA , a spot is visible at the bottom left side of the HWS coordinates. The plan is to move the spot on ITMX up and down by a few millimeters, but yesterday afternoon, we only moved the spot up (pitch) as seen by the BS camera because IFO lost the lock due to the weather. The spot move test started at around 19:29 UTC on 08/14/2024 and lasted about 100 minutes. Since the spot cannot be moved directly on ITMs, we adjusted it on BS. The spot move was done in 4 steps of 1 pixel each, which, according to the camera calibration, is about 6-7 mm. Refer to images 72W_nominal_BS and 72W_6mmup_BS . After adjusting the beam position up in the camera, we didn't realign the CO2X annular on ITMX. The misalignment between the IFO beam and CO2X could be causing some of the changes seen in the signals on the plot attached. We then moved back to the nominal position and attempted to move the beam in the opposite direction. The spot move test had different effects on the signals, as seen in the plot : The ITMX spherical power, as measured by the HWS, decreased by approximately 15 uD (double-passed thermal lens) The impact on ITMY spherical power was minimal, with only an increase of around 2 uD (double-passed). The effect on the optical gain Kappa_C also appeared minimal, with a less than 1% loss. The sideband buildup did not seem to be affected much, as RF18 and RF90 decreased between 3-5% over the test. The signals are calibrated in the attached plot. PRC gain went down from a nominal 42.4 to somewhere around 42. The reflection from the IFO didn't care that much, as the REFL DC signal barely moved. The coupling to high-frequency noise also started to decrease as we moved the beam back to the nominal position. Today, we plan to move the beam position in the opposite direction as we did yesterday. TCS ","{'term': 'L1 ISC', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: karla.ramirez@ligo.org

Report ID: 72660

[Anamaria, Karla]

Yesterday, during the commissioning period, we adjusted the position of the spot on ITMX to see how it affects optical gain and sideband buildup and map the relation between the camera and HWS. The Interferometer (IFO) has been consistently operating at 72W input power. The images from the HWS sensor at ITMX show the presence of a "point absorber." In the image ITMX_PA, a spot is visible at the bottom left side of the HWS coordinates. The plan is to move the spot on ITMX up and down by a few millimeters, but yesterday afternoon, we only moved the spot up (pitch) as seen by the BS camera because IFO lost the lock due to the weather.

The spot move test started at around 19:29 UTC on 08/14/2024 and lasted about 100 minutes. Since the spot cannot be moved directly on ITMs, we adjusted it on BS. The spot move was done in 4 steps of 1 pixel each, which, according to the camera calibration, is about 6-7 mm. Refer to images 72W_nominal_BS and 72W_6mmup_BS. After adjusting the beam position up in the camera, we didn't realign the CO2X annular on ITMX. The misalignment between the IFO beam and CO2X could be causing some of the changes seen in the signals on the plot attached. We then moved back to the nominal position and attempted to move the beam in the opposite direction.
The spot move test had different effects on the signals, as seen in the plot:

column2: • The ITMX spherical power, as measured by the HWS, decreased by approximately 15 uD (double-passed thermal lens)
• The impact on ITMY spherical power was minimal, with only an increase of around 2 uD (double-passed).
• The effect on the optical gain Kappa_C also appeared minimal, with a less than 1% loss.
• The sideband buildup did not seem to be affected much, as RF18 and RF90 decreased between 3-5% over the test. The signals are calibrated in the attached plot.
• PRC gain went down from a nominal 42.4 to somewhere around 42.
• The reflection from the IFO didn't care that much, as the REFL DC signal barely moved.
• The coupling to high-frequency noise also started to decrease as we moved the beam back to the nominal position.

column1: Today, we plan to move the beam position in the opposite direction as we did yesterday.

359,108,L1 ISC - X end temperature change improves range,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72672,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Thu, 15 Aug 2024 11:38:36 -0500","[Anamaria, Dave B, Joe B]The change to the X end temperature that Anamaria requested had a very quick effect on the range, faster than we expected, although it is definitely a welcome improvement. We're trying to work out physically what a change on the order of an hour implies, but our current thinking is something outside of the chamber is the source of the noise rather than, say thermal effects directly on the suspension.I attach a screenshot of the GDS range, the 302 temperature sensor (inside the X end VEA), the 305 temperature sensor (the electronics room next to the LVEA), and the vertical OSEM DOF of the ETMX suspension (which reacts to the thermal expansion or contraction of the suspension itself). Normally time zero would be roughly the worst time day (as seen around -1 day mark), but the temperature change turned it around all the way up to 170 MPC or so. ","{'term': 'L1 ISC', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org

Report ID: 72672

[Anamaria, Dave B, Joe B]

The change to the X end temperature that Anamaria requested had a very quick effect on the range, faster than we expected, although it is definitely a welcome improvement.  We're trying to work out physically what a change on the order of an hour implies, but our current thinking is something outside of the chamber is the source of the noise rather than, say thermal effects directly on the suspension.

I attach a screenshot of the GDS range, the 302 temperature sensor (inside the X end VEA), the 305 temperature sensor (the electronics room next to the LVEA), and the vertical OSEM DOF of the ETMX suspension (which reacts to the thermal expansion or contraction of the suspension itself).  Normally time zero would be roughly the worst time day (as seen around -1 day mark), but the temperature change turned it around all the way up to 170 MPC or so.

375,124,"L1 SUS - Comment to Low range, sqz on off test: It's not the squeezer",https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72655,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Wed, 14 Aug 2024 15:31:26 -0500","I noticed excess noise in some of the SRM/SR3 M2/M3 suspension channels, and so I made some spectra and spectrograms during times when we had these large range drops. The first pdf shows 10 min spectra on August 10th, 11th, 12th, and 14th. I was pretty consistently seeing noise mostly in L1:SUS-SRM_M2_NOISEMON_LR_OUT_DQ, L1:SUS-SRM_M2_NOISEMON_UR_OUT_DQ, L1:SUS-SR3_M3_NOISEMON_LL_OUT_DQ, L1:SUS-SR3_M3_NOISEMON_UL_OUT_DQ, and L1:SUS-SR3_M3_NOISEMON_UR_OUT_DQ. I then made longer duration spectrograms of the noise on August 10th from ~8-14 UTC to see if I could catch the noise in transition to see if it is related to the range drops, which are in the second pdf. It is a bit hard to resolve some of the noise because there are some line artifacts that pop up around 80hz or so. The most noise seems to be in the SRM_M2_LR noisemon, which is consistent with what I saw in the spectra. However, the noise in the spectrograms doesn't really line up with when the range starts dropping, so it's unlikely that some coil/dac noise here is the problem. Detchar Non-image files attached to this report SRMandSR3spectra.pdf SRM_SR3M2_M3Aug10thspectrograms.pdf ","{'term': 'L1 SUS', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: jane.glanzer@ligo.org

Report ID: 72655

I noticed excess noise in some of the SRM/SR3 M2/M3 suspension channels, and so I made some spectra and spectrograms during times when we had these large range drops. The first pdf shows 10 min spectra on August 10th, 11th, 12th, and 14th. I was pretty consistently seeing noise mostly in L1:SUS-SRM_M2_NOISEMON_LR_OUT_DQ, L1:SUS-SRM_M2_NOISEMON_UR_OUT_DQ, L1:SUS-SR3_M3_NOISEMON_LL_OUT_DQ, L1:SUS-SR3_M3_NOISEMON_UL_OUT_DQ, and L1:SUS-SR3_M3_NOISEMON_UR_OUT_DQ. I then made longer duration spectrograms of the noise on August 10th from ~8-14 UTC to see if I could catch the noise in transition to see if it is related to the range drops, which are in the second pdf. It is a bit hard to resolve some of the noise because there are some line artifacts that pop up around 80hz or so. The most noise seems to be in the SRM_M2_LR noisemon, which is consistent with what I saw in the spectra. However, the noise in the spectrograms doesn't really line up with when the range starts dropping, so it's unlikely that some coil/dac noise here is the problem.

377,126,L1 CAL - Comment to Prepared model change for l1calcs,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72653,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Wed, 14 Aug 2024 12:38:51 -0500","I confirmed the new limiter and channel work. However it has exposed a minor bug. The L1:CAL-CS_TDEP_{PCAL,SUS}_LINE*_COH_STRIDE channels (i.e. the stride in seconds between sampling the output of the I and Q demods) is being used as the number of averages (aka buffer size), while the _BUFFSIZE is being used for the stride. This isn't a big problem, as we're still calculating coherence, just with only 10 averages, and the coherence is dividing the actual number of averages, so its a true measure, but we could do better, and would have some issues associated with different low pass choices on the demodulated channels.I'll coordinate with LHO on fixing this next week during maintenance.CAL","{'term': 'L1 CAL', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org

Report ID: 72653

I confirmed the new limiter and channel work. However it has exposed a minor bug. The L1:CAL-CS_TDEP_{PCAL,SUS}_LINE*_COH_STRIDE channels (i.e. the stride in seconds between sampling the output of the I and Q demods) is being used as the number of averages (aka buffer size), while the _BUFFSIZE is being used for the stride. This isn't a big problem, as we're still calculating coherence, just with only 10 averages, and the coherence is dividing the actual number of averages, so its a true measure, but we could do better, and would have some issues associated with different low pass choices on the demodulated channels.
I'll coordinate with LHO on fixing this next week during maintenance.CAL",72653,joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org

378,127,L1 SUS - A2L residual coherence,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72652,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Wed, 14 Aug 2024 12:13:38 -0500","The DIAG_COH guardian started reporting just before we went down for maintenance that the all four quads L2 P2L had higher residual coherence than normal. This is coherence between the ISCINF_P path for each quad to DARM. These measurements are made roughly every 3 hours while in the low noise state.This is the reason for the DIAG_MAIN message of ""FF_COH: More than 3 components of the DIAG COH are high"". Interestingly, the L2 Y2L was higher than its thresholds for two measurement periods. The P2L seems to be consistently higher for a bit more than a day at this point.I've plotted the last 130 days worth of measurement, and we can see some larger variation starting roughly 36 days ago, and sharp uptick for the last day. Unfortunately, I don't see a strong correlation with our daily range variations, so I don't think this is directly related.Given the recent worse performance compared to the good stretch from 90 to 40 days ago, we should look at our A2L decoupling.ISC, SUS ","{'term': 'L1 SUS', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org

Report ID: 72652

The DIAG_COH guardian started reporting just before we went down for maintenance that the all four quads L2 P2L had higher residual coherence than normal. This is coherence between the ISCINF_P path for each quad to DARM. These measurements are made roughly every 3 hours while in the low noise state.

This is the reason for the DIAG_MAIN message of ""FF_COH: More than 3 components of the DIAG COH are high"".  Interestingly, the L2 Y2L was higher than its thresholds for two measurement periods.  The P2L seems to be consistently higher for a bit more than a day at this point.

I've plotted the last 130 days worth of measurement, and we can see some larger variation starting roughly 36 days ago, and sharp uptick for the last day.  Unfortunately, I don't see a strong correlation with our daily range variations, so I don't think this is directly related.
Given the recent worse performance compared to the good stretch from 90 to 40 days ago, we should look at our A2L decoupling.ISC, SUS

Author: robert.cottingham@ligo.org

Report ID: 72649

Bob C.

During maintenance, checked hot soak pressure after one week in the Y-mid RGA bake was 1.2E(-7) Torr.  Gatevalve was 119°C, RGA manifold reported 201°C and 196°C, all within normal temperature hysteresis for these types of controllers.

The pressure in the Y-arm around the midstation are nearly to baseline pressure after a week.  A gauge at the Y-mid is within line of sight of a hot flange so the pressure last week was very elevated.

Bob C.

Yesterday during maintenance period, all of the newer MKS 390 Series Micro-ATM gauges were inspected to determine if any filaments were out and the gauges were running on their second filament.  These were on the HAM5/7 relay tube, HAM7, FC tube, and HAM8.

PT-152, PT-153, PT-154, PT-155, PT-156, PT-157, PT-158, and PT-159 all indicated both fillaments were working.  All gauges had normal readings in CDS and had blinking green status light indicating normal function.

Author: janos.csizmazia@ligo.org

Report ID: 79615

Today's activities:

- After the replacement of the PT-154 gauge (https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79599), and after the small volume of the gauge was pumped overnight, now it has been valved together with the main volume
- The small Pfeiffer turbo, along with the leak checker was taken off from the gauge's volume
- Then, the HAM7-BSC3 small FCT section was valved together with HAM7 - FCV-1 opened
- The 2 aux carts have been taken off from the HAM5/HAM6 annulus system
- An aux cart was added to GV7 for safety reasons, to protect its annulus system during opening it up

- The HAM6 turbo was valved out. The reason for valving it out so early is that the backing scroll pump had horrendous noise, so it needs rebuilding, and would have not been a good decision to let it run overnight. Especially, that the backing pressure was slowly growing. The hoses, cables, and the cart was also put away
- RGA scans were collected at the corner, before opening up the large gate valves - GV5 and GV7. The results will be posted to the comment section",79615,janos.csizmazia@ligo.org

Author: jim.warner@ligo.org

Report ID: 79613

Yesterday morning I unlocked HAM5&6 HEPIs, unaware that VAC needed back up on that chamber to disconnect turbos. This afternoon, Mitch and Ibrahim helped me re-lock those HEPIs. Because we didn't think any alignment work would be needed before unlocking again, we didn't use the normal procedure to try to preserve HEPI position, I just turned off the loops and we engaged the stops. Even so, the biggest offsets from operating position are less than 50 um/urad, most are more like 10.

",79613,jim.warner@ligo.org

Author: francisco.llamas@ligo.org

Report ID: 79608

MiriamR, RickS, TonyS, FranciscoL

On Monday, August 19, we moved the X-End pcal inner beam to be centered on the Rx input port. The previous configuration had the inner beam to the right of the Rx input port by 5mm. We centered the beam to the desigated position before the interferometer resumes the obsevation run.
Note: Screwing the yaw-adjuster in a clock-wise motion moves the beam from the right side of the target to the center (goes to the left).

The voltage from BothBeamsBefore.jpg was of 3.383 V as measured with a hanheld voltmeter, after moving the beams (see BothBeamsAfter.jpg) the voltage was of 3.384. EndStationLog.pdf has a list of voltage values with the corresponding times (local timezone) at which they were measured.

Author: david.barker@ligo.org

Report ID: 79611

Janos, Dave:
After review of the current pressure alarms, we came up with the following changes:
1. Janos requested that PT120B (BSC2-BS) be replaced with PT132_MOD2 (BSC3-ITMX). The latter is a less noisy signal.
2. For alarms where the high level is an order of magnitude greater than the signal average, reduce the high to be about 3*avg
These changes were made and installed at 13:50 during the reboot of cdslogin.
To help with the review of the vacuum alarms I wrote a python program which compares the alarm HIGH value with a hours worth of minute trend data (AVG and MAX). If MAX/HIGH > 10 it flags the channel.

Using the two picomotor-controlled mirrors in the FSS path, I was only able to increase the signal from 0.54V to 0.66V , which is much less than I was hoping for. I'm still seeing what looks like a pitch misalignment on the RefCav REFL camera, but any further adjustment with the picos doesn't seem to be providing much more improvement on the TPD, so we'll likely need to go into the enclosure for some on-table alignment in the future to improve the alignment further. Author: ryan.short@ligo.org

Report ID: 79607

This morning, I attempted to improve the FSS RefCav alignment as the signal on the trans TPD has been falling over the past month. Using the two picomotor-controlled mirrors in the FSS path, I was only able to increase the signal from 0.54V to 0.66V, which is much less than I was hoping for. I'm still seeing what looks like a pitch misalignment on the RefCav REFL camera, but any further adjustment with the picos doesn't seem to be providing much more improvement on the TPD, so we'll likely need to go into the enclosure for some on-table alignment in the future to improve the alignment further.

793,0,H1 PEM - Magnetic Injection Suite is Working,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79605,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Tue, 20 Aug 2024 09:16:58 -0700","This morning, I manually ran through the usual magnetic injection suite (21 total injections across all stations) that's run before Tuesday maintenance during normal observing times to verify things were working. The only hiccup I encountered was that none of the injections at EX seemed to run; the amplifiers turned on correctly, the correct filter modules were applied, and Guardian showed no errors, but the magnetometers gave no response when the injection was supposed to start and I saw no signal in the appropriate _EXCMON channels. After conversing with Dave and Erik and seeing there was no problem starting a manual excitation, they suggested that the PEM_MAG_INJ Guardian likely needed to be restarted to re-establish connection with the frontends at EX since some of them were restarted in June. After restarting the node, I ran through the suite again and there were no issues. The last successful test ran from 1408203575 to 1408204731 (about 22 minutes), and I've left the Guardian in WAITING.","{'term': 'H1 PEM', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: ryan.short@ligo.org

Report ID: 79605

This morning, I manually ran through the usual magnetic injection suite (21 total injections across all stations) that's run before Tuesday maintenance during normal observing times to verify things were working. The only hiccup I encountered was that none of the injections at EX seemed to run; the amplifiers turned on correctly, the correct filter modules were applied, and Guardian showed no errors, but the magnetometers gave no response when the injection was supposed to start and I saw no signal in the appropriate _EXCMON channels. After conversing with Dave and Erik and seeing there was no problem starting a manual excitation, they suggested that the PEM_MAG_INJ Guardian likely needed to be restarted to re-establish connection with the frontends at EX since some of them were restarted in June. After restarting the node, I ran through the suite again and there were no issues.

The last successful test ran from 1408203575 to 1408204731 (about 22 minutes), and I've left the Guardian in WAITING.

",79605,ryan.short@ligo.org

Author: janos.csizmazia@ligo.org

Report ID: 79599

Jordan V., Gerardo M., Travis S., Janos Cs.

The PT-154 MKS wide range gauge was replaced due to failure, on the small FCT section between HAM7 and BSC3. Its small volume is being pumped down. As the pressure of that FCT section between GVs FCV-1 and FCV-2 is supposedly around 1-2E-8 Torr, it will be pumped overnight. Now it is at 6.1E-8 Torr. Tomorrow it will be valved in to the main volume. After this, this small FCT section will be valved together with HAM7 and the relay tube (FCV-1 to be opened).
Leak check was also done, and no leak bigger than 1E-10 Torr was detected.

Author: camilla.compton@ligo.org

Report ID: 79592

Naoki, Camilla.

After SQZ laser was turned on laser week, today we locked PMC and SHG with no issues. We struggled with OPO locking (CLF dual). In the end Naoki could lock by hand but the trigger wasn't triggering. We will continue to troubleshoot tomorrow.  The OPO dither lock  worked well but only after we swapped H1:SQZ-OPO_IR_LSC_SERVO_GAIN sign from -10 to 10: strange!

I put ZM4/5 PSAMS and ZM4/5/6, ZM2/3 and FC1 alignments back to the same values as in alog79193. Todays plot and July 17th plot attached. There was only around 0.3mW on the IR trans, when we expect 1mW. So may need some more alignment moved. We have the SQZT7 iris to help if needed.

802,0,H1 SUS - In-Lock SUS Charge Measurements ITMX Mystery Solved,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79597,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Mon, 19 Aug 2024 16:49:15 -0700","Camilla, Oli We looked into the weird results we were seeing in the ITMX In-Lock SUS charge measurements. The coherence when the bias is on for both the bias and length drives is always good, but the coherences are bad (usually below 0.09) for both bias and length drives when the excitations run with the bias off. I compared the differences in the coherence value outputs in the python script versus the matlab script( screenshot ), and although the values are calculated slightly differently and are not exactly the same, they are resonably close enough that we can say that there is not an issue with how we are calculating the coherences. Next, we used ndscope to look at the latest excitations and measurements from July 09th (ndscope-bais on , ndscope-bias off ). Plotting L3_LOCK_BIAS_OUTPUT, L3_DRIVEALIGN_L2L_OUTPUT, L3_LVESDAMON_UL_OUT_DQ, and L3_ESDAMON_DC_OUT_DQ for both ITMX and ITMY, if there was an issue with the excitations not going through, we would expect to see nothing on the ESDAMON and LVESDAMON channels, but we do see them on ITMX. We were still confused as to why we would see the excitations go through the ESDAMON channels but still have such low coherence, so we compared the ITMX measurements to ITMY on dtt for the July 09th measurements looking at how each excitation showed up in DARM and what the coherence was. When the bias was on, both the bias drive and Length drive measurements look as we expect, with the drive in their respective channels, a peak seen in DARM at that frequency, and a coherence of 1 at that frequency( bias_drive_bias_on , length_drive_bias_on ). However, in the comparisons with the bias off, we can see the excitations in their channels for both ITMX and ITMY, but while ITMY has the peak in DARM like the bias on measurements, ITMX is missing this peak in DARM( bias_drive_bias_off , length_drive_bias_off ). The coherence between DARM and the excitation channel is also not 1 on ITMX. We showed these results to Sheila and she said that these results for ITMX with the bias off make sense if there is no charge built up on the ITM, which would be the first time this has been the case! So there are no issues with the excitations or script thankfully. We will be making changes to the analysis script to still run the analysis even if the coherence is low, and will be adding a note explaining what that means. ","{'term': 'H1 SUS', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: oli.patane@ligo.org

Report ID: 79597

Camilla, Oli

We looked into the weird results we were seeing in the ITMX In-Lock SUS charge measurements. The coherence when the bias is on for both the bias and length drives is always good, but the coherences are bad (usually below 0.09) for both bias and length drives when the excitations run with the bias off.

I compared the differences in the coherence value outputs in the python script versus the matlab script(screenshot), and although the values are calculated slightly differently and are not exactly the same, they are resonably close enough that we can say that there is not an issue with how we are calculating the coherences.

Next, we used ndscope to look at the latest excitations and measurements from July 09th (ndscope-bais on, ndscope-bias off). Plotting L3_LOCK_BIAS_OUTPUT, L3_DRIVEALIGN_L2L_OUTPUT, L3_LVESDAMON_UL_OUT_DQ, and L3_ESDAMON_DC_OUT_DQ for both ITMX and ITMY, if there was an issue with the excitations not going through, we would expect to see nothing on the ESDAMON and LVESDAMON channels, but we do see them on ITMX.

We were still confused as to why we would see the excitations go through the ESDAMON channels but still have such low coherence, so we compared the ITMX measurements to ITMY on dtt for the July 09th measurements looking at how each excitation showed up in DARM and what the coherence was. When the bias was on, both the bias drive and Length drive measurements look as we expect, with the drive in their respective channels, a peak seen in DARM at that frequency, and a coherence of 1 at that frequency(bias_drive_bias_on, length_drive_bias_on). However, in the comparisons with the bias off, we can see the excitations in their channels for both ITMX and ITMY, but while ITMY has the peak in DARM like the bias on measurements, ITMX is missing this peak in DARM(bias_drive_bias_off, length_drive_bias_off). The coherence between DARM and the excitation channel is also not 1 on ITMX.

We showed these results to Sheila and she said that these results for ITMX with the bias off make sense if there is no charge built up on the ITM, which would be the first time this has been the case! So there are no issues with the excitations or script thankfully.
We will be making changes to the analysis script to still run the analysis even if the coherence is low, and will be adding a note explaining what that means.

803,0,H1 PSL - Rewritten PSL Rotation Stage Calibration Scripts,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79596,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Mon, 19 Aug 2024 16:02:34 -0700","I've combined the existing Python and MATLAB scripts that are used for calibrating the PSL rotation stage into one cohesive, cleaner Python script: /opt/rtcds/userapps/release/psl/h1/scripts/RotationStage/CalibRotStage.py The script takes two arguments to run the full process of sweeping the stage and running the calibration fitting: python CalibRotStage.py -m -c To skip the rotation stage sweep or calibration fitting steps, simply omit the -m or -c arguments, respectively. The full process for running a PSL rotation stage calibration now goes as follows: Take IMC offline and pause LASER_PWR Guardian Run the calibration script as stated above with both arguments Input the new calibration coefficients into the calibration medm and accept these in SDF Relock IMC and resume LASER_PWR Guardian ","{'term': 'H1 PSL', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: ryan.short@ligo.org

Report ID: 79596

I've combined the existing Python and MATLAB scripts that are used for calibrating the PSL rotation stage into one cohesive, cleaner Python script: /opt/rtcds/userapps/release/psl/h1/scripts/RotationStage/CalibRotStage.py
The script takes two arguments to run the full process of sweeping the stage and running the calibration fitting: python CalibRotStage.py -m -c
To skip the rotation stage sweep or calibration fitting steps, simply omit the -m or -c arguments, respectively.
The full process for running a PSL rotation stage calibration now goes as follows:

column2: • Take IMC offline and pause LASER_PWR Guardian
• Run the calibration script as stated above with both arguments
• Input the new calibration coefficients into the calibration medm and accept these in SDF

Author: jeffrey.kissel@ligo.org

Report ID: 79594

J. Kissel

Conversations are still brewing about what to do about DuoTone timing signals showing up in DARM -- presumably through the OMC DCPD's ADC card (see LHO:77579). Recall that we've narrowed down the coupling mechanism to direct channel-to-channel cross coupling within the ADC (see LHO:78238). As such, one of the options on the table is to reduce the amplitude of the DuoTone timing signal, which is using 1/4 of the ADC channel's range at 5 [V_pp], rather loud, IMHO (see LHO:78218).

Daniel and Erik did a whole bunch of work at the start of O4 to get the front-end-code computed ADC timing measure more accurately reporting and answer with a better algorithm in the front-end (see LHO:67693 and LHO:67545), so I figured I show the trend of a few important front-end's answers, since I haven't seen such a trend:
(1) the h1omc0 segregated IO chassis which houses the GW DCPDs,
(2) the h1lsc0 computer which *used* to house the DCPDs prior to O4.
(3 & 4) the two end-station ISC computers which house, among other things, the PCAL systems.
where I'm eye-balling (via y-cursor at least) the long-term trend of the mean, the middle of the max/min excursions, and the worst of the max/min excursions.
These answers (the means) are all expected, but it's good to have some numbers on the max / min excursions, which are, presumably, noise.
Zoom in closer, one can see on the minute time scale trend of a gravitational wave event, the estimation of the timing error is about as precise.

806,0,H1 PSL - PSL Control Box 1 Moved to Separate Power Supply (WP 12051),https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79593,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Mon, 19 Aug 2024 14:22:16 -0700","R. Short, F. Clara In the ongoing effort to mitigate the 9.5Hz comb recently found to be coming from the PSL flow meters ( alog79533 ), this afternoon Fil put the PSL control box in the LVEA PSL racks on its own, separate 24V bench-top power supply. Once I shut down the PSL in a controlled manner (in order of ISS, FSS, PMC, AMP2, AMP1, NPRO, chiller), Fil switched CB1 to the separate power supply, then I brought the system back up without any issues. I'm leaving the ISS off for now while the system warms back up. I'm leaving WP12051 open for now until enough data can be collected to say whether this separate supply helps the 9.5Hz comb or not. Please be aware of the new power supply cable running from under the table outside the PSL enclosure to behind the racks; Fil placed a cone here to warn of the potential trip hazard. DetChar","{'term': 'H1 PSL', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: ryan.short@ligo.org

Report ID: 79593

R. Short, F. Clara

In the ongoing effort to mitigate the 9.5Hz comb recently found to be coming from the PSL flow meters (alog79533), this afternoon Fil put the PSL control box in the LVEA PSL racks on its own, separate 24V bench-top power supply. Once I shut down the PSL in a controlled manner (in order of ISS, FSS, PMC, AMP2, AMP1, NPRO, chiller), Fil switched CB1 to the separate power supply, then I brought the system back up without any issues. I'm leaving the ISS off for now while the system warms back up. I'm leaving WP12051 open for now until enough data can be collected to say whether this separate supply helps the 9.5Hz comb or not.
Please be aware of the new power supply cable running from under the table outside the PSL enclosure to behind the racks; Fil placed a cone here to warn of the potential trip hazard.

Author: ryan.short@ligo.org

Report ID: 79590

FAMIS 21188
The PSL was taken down last Tuesday as part of Jason and Fil's comb hunt (alog79533), which shows in basically every trend six days ago.

The ISS was not turned back on when the PSL was brought back up last week, so Jason enabled it this morning, which explains the lower PMC transmitted power over the past week or so. However, even with the ISS now on, the PMC is putting out ~1.6W less power compared to before it was unlocked last week.
The FSS TPD has been trending down over the past several weeks and alignment looks poor on the camera, so sometime today or tomorrow I'll touch up the RefCav alignment.

[TJ, Joe B]

We installed a new PD after the PCALY laser but before the AOM, as a proof of principle and help diagnose if we have a future PCAL failure whether it is AOM or laser related.  I used a PD100A from the optics lab. It was setup such that the reflection from the PD is sent to a razor blade beam dump (which the PD replaced).

The Y end VEA is going to need to remain laser hazard until I get a proper feedthrough setup for the box, hopefully by next Tuesday, or if needed, I can remove the cables sooner to able to transition.  Right now the top is simply laying on top and not fully screwed down to allow the cables out.
It is currently reading out of the working standard path (which is unused most of the time), L1:CAL-PCALY_WS_PD_OUTPUT.CAL",72774,joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org
