Author: joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org

Report ID: 72773

[Vlad B, Joe B]

We measured the ETMX PUM coil driver in situ. Based on my advice from last time, see LLO alog 58800, we decided to do a quicker set of measurements, from 1 to 10 kHz, with a 20 ohm resistor as the load. We had some issues resurrecting the gpib scripts, so ended up just using a USB stick to get the data of the SR785. Also, as a reminder to our future selves, make sure the range is set properly before hand so it doesn't autorange and give you disjoint data at the half a percent level.
Vlad used IIRational to do the fitting and then update the filters in the L1SUSETMX filter file.

Data is in the usual calibration location: /ligo/svncommon/CalSVN/aligocalibration/trunk/Common/Electronics/L1/Data/SUSElectronics/ETMX/PUM/2024-08-20/.  Plots of data versus fits are in a sub-directory there, and attached as pdfs.  Fitting script is also in the directory, called process_TFs_to_Fit.pyCAL, SUS

Today, we installed the IR sensor on the viewport housing used for ITMX CO2 (BSC3 C0G5) according to drawing LIGO-D1101627. After that, we connected the IR sensor to the TCS IR comparator box D1300366-v1 SN S1301785 (aka IR sensor box).

Additionally, we set up temporary monitoring for the IR sensor box. This setup is similar to the one used for Y. We connected a breakout board to the IR sensor box. We used Pin 2 from the breakout board and a pickoff from the Vin (TP3) point from the board D1300249-v3. We repurposed the L1:PEM-CS_ADC_4_26_OUT_DQ channel to monitor the IR sensor channel. The voltage measured from the monitoring test point was +1mV. Refer to the 4rd attached picture for more details on how we connected the signal pickoff to the box.

858,0,L1 SEI - Comment to L1 HAM6 CPS nonstationary noise is back,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72767,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Tue, 20 Aug 2024 12:46:46 -0500","[ WP 11718 ] The noise has become more intermittent after the site power outage on last Thursday ( alog 72679 ), which means it comes and goes at a more arrupted rate. It has not been present today during the Maintenance period. My initial plan was to looking at the CPS field chassis at corner 3, because the noise signal is the largest at CPS in that corner, as can be seen in the plots in alog above. Now the noise is not present but there is still some lines at high frequency (around 1400Hz) at corner 3 CPS, so I still came out on the floor and check the field box. After unplug and reconnect power & synch cables, the lines have disappeared, see figure1 . I also noticed the ground cable from corner 3 field chassis to chamber was not connected, this probably has been like this since the flange had the T connector hooked up and the sub-flange covers (where the ground cable used to attached to) got removed. I re-attached this cable to chamber with a aligator clip, see pic2 . I'll continue monitor, and hopefully either the noise will not come back or come back and give us time to get to it and debug. ","{'term': 'L1 SEI', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: huyen.pham@ligo.org

Report ID: 72767

[WP 11718]

The noise has become more intermittent after the site power outage on last Thursday (alog 72679), which means it comes and goes at a more arrupted rate. It has not been present today during the Maintenance period. My initial plan was to looking at the CPS field chassis at corner 3, because the noise signal is the largest at CPS in that corner, as can be seen in the plots in alog above.

Now the noise is not present but there is still some lines at high frequency (around 1400Hz) at corner 3 CPS, so I still came out on the floor and check the field box. After unplug and reconnect power & synch cables, the lines have disappeared, see figure1. I also noticed the ground cable from corner 3 field chassis to chamber was not connected, this probably has been like this since the flange had the T connector hooked up and the sub-flange covers (where the ground cable used to attached to) got removed. I re-attached this cable to chamber with a aligator clip, see pic2.
I'll continue monitor, and hopefully either the noise will not come back or come back and give us time to get to it and debug.

Quickly looking around at components which are likely to have gone bad: Laser, AOM, AOM Driver. Laser was left on (both PcalY and PcalX incident). The fact that the issue is no longer present seems to suggest that the laser is not the cause. AOM crystals and local electronics are generally quite rugged and this is an unlikely common point of failure. AOM drivers are both within a chassis with poor ventilation and I observed no heat sink. The specs for the most recent AOM drivers from the manufacturer [ 532C and 532F (we used 532B, obsolete)] indicate a heat-sink must be present and temperatures must not exceed 70 C. I found it unusual that the AOM drivers have no heat-sinks as that is the norm. I have put the PcalY in the state where we left it over Sunday: Laser on and shuttered, and otherwise no oscillations sent to the AOM Driver. During tomorrow Tuesday maintenance we will check the temperatures of the currently running PcalX and not running PcalY to see if the driver temperature is the issue. It should be moderately easy to cut a hole in the chassis and mount heat sinks in the relevant locations. Ambient cooling with the cold VEAs should be sufficient. We are also planning to install some PDs to monitor the input laser light on our PDs, to try and tell the difference between AOM and Laser issues.","{'term': 'L1 OpsInfo', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: vladimir.bossilkov@ligo.org

Report ID: 72747

[Joe B, Vlad B]

Much like the very similar issue we had with PcalX [71857], leaving the PcalY non operating (i.e. shuttered but the laser otherwise left on) the problem had resolved itself when we turned everything on again today.
Quickly looking around at components which are likely to have gone bad: Laser, AOM, AOM Driver.

column2: • Laser was left on (both PcalY and PcalX incident). The fact that the issue is no longer present seems to suggest that the laser is not the cause.
• AOM crystals and local electronics are generally quite rugged and this is an unlikely common point of failure.

• AOM drivers are both within a chassis with poor ventilation and I observed no heat sink. The specs for the most recent AOM drivers from the manufacturer [532C and 532F (we used 532B, obsolete)] indicate a heat-sink must be present and temperatures must not exceed 70 C. I found it unusual that the AOM drivers have no heat-sinks as that is the norm.

column1: I have put the PcalY in the state where we left it over Sunday: Laser on and shuttered, and otherwise no oscillations sent to the AOM Driver. During tomorrow Tuesday maintenance we will check the temperatures of the currently running PcalX and not running PcalY to see if the driver temperature is the issue.
It should be moderately easy to cut a hole in the chassis and mount heat sinks in the relevant locations. Ambient cooling with the cold VEAs should be sufficient.

We are also planning to install some PDs to monitor the input laser light on our PDs, to try and tell the difference between AOM and Laser issues.

",72747,vladimir.bossilkov@ligo.org

Author: begum.kabagoz@ligo.org

Report ID: 72729

[Begum, David, Valera]

On Jul 31, after the recovery of CO2 lasers, we optimized squeezing with fine alignment and improved it from -5.3 dB (we'll call this Alignment A) to -5.6 dB (Alignment B), see alog 72441. Valera pointed out that aside from the squeezing level, there seemed to be an improvement in the 30-100 Hz band too. Our operating assumption has been that the quantum noise has little effect on low frequency region. So, we decided to test this out by reverting the alignment back to Alignment A on August 1st and recording spectra. Suprisingly, this on-off test showed the extra 30-100 Hz noise was indeed due to Alignment A. [Note: this is different from the low frequnecy noise that has been plaguing us sporadically, reducing our range, see alog 72583]

Attached plot shows the two dates with Alignment A and B, showing the same behavior. Note that the improvement in high frequency squeezing and 30-100 Hz band goes together, so we'll keep trusting our alignment strategy (which optimizes for 2kHz sqz) to give us the optimal quantum noise across the entire 20-4000 Hz band.

To see if we can account for the low frequency noise with a GWINC quantum noise budget, we took spectra with different squeezing angles for Alignment A and B. The quantum noise projections for Alignment A and Alignment B for various sqz angles are attached. Also see squeezing data, quantum noise model and total noise budgets for A and B. A comparison plot for the two alignments and their associated quantum noise curves are also attached here. Since the only thing changing between the two cases is the alignment of the sqz beam, we used SQZ to OMC (and in extension SQZ to IFO mode-matching) parameters as the free parameters between the two models. Note, the sqz to ifo mode mismatch parameter was essential for fitting low frequency region. The starting mode was based on alog 72283.
17:25:14 UTC --> Alignment A, mid sqz, CLF 150 º, 5 minutes

Author: matthew.heintze@ligo.org

Report ID: 72745

Aidan, Matt
There had been some questions to me regarding the history of the IR sensor for TCS CO2 system. I met with Aidan to discuss this and below are some cliff notes from our chat:
* The IR sensor is in case an insect or something lands on the the viewport and contaminate forms on there creating more scatter that we could monitor.

* The final design document for the TCS CO2 laser projection system (T1100570-V5) section 7.3.11 (page 32) has a brief comment on the IR sensor "The ZnSe viewports will use an IR sensor to look for stray IR reflections (caused by sudden large
scattering sources on the viewports, for example, insects settling on the ZnSe). This unit has a setpoint above which the laser interlock will be triggered."
* How the IR sensor is mounted to the viewport housing can be seen in D1101627-V4 on Sheet 1. This is a double viewport

* The justification behind why the IR sensor was put in place is from the recommendation of T1100644-V2 Finding #3 of the main document in the file card "Recommendation: Class 4 laser relay optics should be designed to preclude foci or regions of

high power density near the vacuum boundary. An engineering hazard analysis may be required for such applications. This should take into account such factors as optical absorption tolerances, potential for acquired contamination, material thermal and mechanical properties, effect of surface and bulk defects, and worst-case power and beam size excursions (including unplanned or exceptional events)."

* There is no set numbers on what we is the trigger level of the this sensor. This is not a calibrated signal as just looks at stray light and will change if there is a power change or an alignment change, this will alter the level it is monitored at.
* The IR sensor was a last minute addition ( the viewport IR sensor and laser temperature sensor share an alarm channel (for historical reasons, due to one being added at the last minute)

Author: joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org

Report ID: 72744

[Vlad B, Joe B]

We went to the Y-End and put a beam dump in before the PCAL beam gets split in 2 to be sent into chamber, but after the TX PD and OFS PD pickoffs.  This let us see the noise spectrum of the PCAL system without affecting the main interferometer.

TX PD spectrum looks fine now.  We tried changing the L1:CAL-PCALY_OPTICALFOLLOWERSERVOOFFSET, and the OFS followed smoothly, with little to no error.  After putting the OFS offset back, we then turned on some typical calibration line values, and the specturm looked perfectly normal.
For now, we've left the system beam dumped, but we can play with the loop during the commissioning period without affecting the interferometer today.

Our current plan for tomorrow is to swap the AOM RF driver with a spare we have on hand, as well as add 1 or 2 more PDs as readbacks for the laser power directly and/or the undiffracted beam from the AOM. We actually should consider doing this for both PCALs.

Author: ryan.short@ligo.org

Report ID: 79779

I've added a change into the H1_MANAGER Guardian that starts a one hour timer when we reach OMC_WHITENING to allow for violin modes to damp down if needed before moving to NLN. While waiting in OMC_WHITENING, the already existing two hour timer to reach NLN once the locking process starts is ignored as violin modes should be damping without the need for intervention. However, once the one hour timer expires, if ISC_LOCK has still not moved to NLN, H1_MANAGER will move to ASSISTANCE_REQ and initiate a call.

I've also removed some lines in the IFO_NOTIFY Guardian which I had added last year (alog72160) that allowed for an additional time after reaching NLN for ADS to converge and switch to camera servos before calling for help. Since the switch from ADS to cameras now happens before reaching NLN, this code is irrelevant.

All of these changes have been saved and loaded.

",79779,ryan.short@ligo.org

Author: elenna.capote@ligo.org

Report ID: 79776

I am not sure how the A2L is run these days, but there is some DARM coherence with DHARD Y that makes me think we should recheck the Y2L gains. See attached screenshot from today's lock.

As a reminder, the work that Gabriele and I did last April found that the DHARD Y coupling had two distinct frequency regimes: a steep low frequency coupling that depended heavily on the AS A WFS yaw offset, and a much flatter coupling about ~30 Hz that depended much more strongly on the Y2L gain of ITMY (this was I think before we started adjusting all the A2L gains on the test masses). Relevant alogs: 76407 and 76363
Based on this coherence, the Y2L gains at least deserve another look. Is it possible to track a DHARD Y injection during the test?

Author: louis.dartez@ligo.org

Report ID: 79764

We have a preliminary report for the calibration status of LHO after the vent recovery, based on the measurement taken in LHO:79691. The report can be found here.

Taking a look at the PCALY to (GDS-CALIB_STRAIN_CLEAN) DARM broadband injection, there is an elevated amount of error between 30 and 60Hz. It would be worth considering to update the calibration at the next available opportunity, but it isn't pushing us beyond 10% mag/10deg phase yet. This is also corroborated by the monitoring page here.
N.B. I used pcal to GDS instead of to DELTAL_EXTERNAL because the GDS channel is already calibrated to meters for us.

Author: elenna.capote@ligo.org

Report ID: 79768

These have now been tested, SRCL passes, MICH fails.

The SRCL screenshot compares Oli's SRCL measurement from four days ago with the "current" filter, and the new "trial" filter that I applied today. There is clear improvement everywhere (except for a small worsening between 100-200 Hz), so I think we should use this filter.

The MICH screenshot compares Oli's MICH measurement from four days ago with the "current" filter, along with "no FF" and "trial". The trial did what I promised, and reduced the coupling between 10-20 Hz, but clearly at the sacrifice of the noise everywhere else. I think we should stay with "current".

I am changing the guardian to select this new SRCL filter (FM5) in "lownoise length control" and the gain back to 1. There will be an SDF observing diff for SRCLFF1 that can be accepted by the operator.

In my opinion the hardest region to fit is between 10-20 Hz because of the presence of some high Q features, such as around 17 Hz. It would be worth considering what is causing those features- perhaps some bounce/roll notches. Do we still need those notches, or could they be briefly turned off during a feedforward injection? That might make the low frequency portion easier to fit and therefore easier to achieve good subtraction 10-30 Hz.

Author: elenna.capote@ligo.org

Report ID: 79767

Here is some more information about the fits.

First, my MICH fit caused a lockloss this morning because I forgot to the check the phase on the filter. Sometimes, the phase gets flipped during the fitting. Usually, I compare the sign of the phase with the previous filter in foton and adjust accordingly, but I forgot to do it this time (rookie mistake). I have double checked the new SRCL filter phase and fixed the MICH phase.

Attached are two screenshots of the fittings. First, the MICH fitting compares the current filter, labeled as "reference 1" with the red trace which represents the new fit. The bottom right plot compares the fit residuals. You can see from this plot that the most improvement occurs at low frequency, with some small improvement at mid frequency. The SRCL fitting has many more traces, but compare the orange "current fit" trace with the trace labeled "best with less HF gain". This has more improvement almost everywhere. There is an increase in gain at high frequency, but it is less than an order of magnitude, so I think it's ok. The new fit also has reduced the high Q feature around 300 Hz that was potentially injecting noise. There is a factor 5-10 improvement between 10-50 Hz that will help the most.

Stopping and starting the node resulted in different channels that it couldn't connect to each time. I've removed this from ISC_LOCK for now, but kept the main function in ISC_library.py. Looking at the FC WFS plot here: summary pages SQZ subsystems you can see that the squeezer whistles have reappeared.  This is a possible explanation for the nonstationarity and poor range of DARM overnight (There's an issue with the summary page of last night's range right now, but it should appear here: range summary.  However, looking at the previous days, the squeezer whistles appeared on the 25th and have been getting more frequent, but we didn't see poor range until last night.
As Ryan Crouch noted, last night was windy, but the wind died down around the time the IFO lost lock, and the last 6 hours have been calm with poor range.

Author: ryan.crouch@ligo.org

Report ID: 79749

TITLE: 08/28 Eve Shift: 2300-0500 UTC (1600-2200 PST), all times posted in UTC

SHIFT SUMMARY: High winds made locking very difficult, they're dying down as the shift is ending and I just finished an IA so I'm hopeful the IFO will be able to lock itself as we just got DRMI offloaded at 05:00UTC

column2: • We managed to lock despite the wind in the late afternoon, and we returned to Observing at 23:30 UTC with a range of about 115. There was a lot of low frequency noise, low frequency coherence with SRCL and CHARD & DHARD both in Y.

• PI 31 started to ring up after a few minutes but SUS_PI was able to successfully damp close to the last second as we were getting DCPD saturations. The GRD had some trouble as it was ringing back up again, Naoki tried increasing the gain. This PI was causing SDF diffs and dropping us from Observing as well.
• The winds were even higher now, gusts over 40 mph and an avg of over 20mph.
• 00:17 UTC I held us in down as the the 5 min avg went up and over 30mph

• While ISC_LOCK was in down, I added a function to ISC_library and a call in to it in ISC_LOCK to run in PREP_FOR_LOCKING to log any and all of the SDF diffs as the tables switch that I've tested in the TEST node. I made sure the 2 codes' svns were up to date before making my changes, so if for some reason these throw an error, we can revert to the previous revision.
• 02:30 UTC I noticed the wind calmed down a bit, so I started trying to lock again
• Had to adjust SRM to lock DRMI

column3: • All the signals on NUC30 looked pretty ratty leading up to this

column2: • 04:20 - 04:40 UTC ran an initial alignment as the ITM error signals have been looking large the past couple tries
• The wind was died down a good amount so I'm hopeful the IFO will lock

Author: elenna.capote@ligo.org

Report ID: 79755

I was able to new SRCL and MICH feedforward using the iterative method. Measurements were taken in alog 79693.
The current MICH FF is performing well except for below 30 Hz, so that's where I targeted in my fit. SRCL needed some improvement everywhere.
The new MICH filter is saved and loaded in FM8 and the new SRCL filter is saved and loaded in FM5. They are both labeled with the date '8-27-24'.
To compare how these filters are performing, I would use the templates Oli saved in the above alog, but first save the live trace as a reference to compare against.

I have not yet done the PRCL fit because I want to see how SRCL performs, and maybe redo the PRCL injections before trying the fit.

",79755,elenna.capote@ligo.org

Author: jenne.driggers@ligo.org

Report ID: 79748

[RyanS, TJ, Jenne]

Some (but not all) of our recent locks have had significant jittering and shaking visible on the OMC Trans camera.  Since it's happening again this lock, I took a look at some of the channels that look at the trans camera readbacks.

The y-cursors are set to the max/min values of the m-trend from right now, when the camera is shaking.  I then scrolled to the recent lock (that ended with maintenance) and show that the variance in all of these channels was much lower in that past lock.

I'm still not sure what is causing this, but at least the size of the fuzz in any of these camera channels can help us see when it is / isn't happening.  My prime suspicion is a loop oscillation in the OMC length loop (that is based entirely on non-scientific gut feelings though).

1154,37,X1 SUS - BBSS Bounce and Roll Modes Measured,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79743,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Tue, 27 Aug 2024 15:51:59 -0700","Ibrahim A, Jeff K On 8/22, Jeff K and I ran some measurements of our assembled BBSS and determined the Bounce and Roll modes to be: Bounce : 19.835 Hz (model prediction: 19.56 Hz) BW: 0.01 (128s/avg) Averages: 50 Excitation Waveform: Uniform Noise, 19-20 Hz Roll : 32.047 Hz (model prediction: 31.88 Hz) BW: 0.001 (1024s/avg) Averages: 50 Excitation Waveform: Uniform Noise, 31-33 Hz Confirmation ASD (exponential avg) Excitation: BW: 0.02 (64s) Excitation Waveform: Sine Averages: 5 I have linked this alog to the SWG Logbook in the case these results are needed for BRD development for the BBSS. Screenshots of these peaks and the excitation spectra are attached and the Data can be found on the X1 (Test Stand) Network: at /ligo/svncommon/SusSVN/sus/trunk/BBSS/X1/BS/Common/Data/ under names: Roll: 2024-08-22_1200_X1SUSBS_M1M2_Roll_V_0p001to40Hz.xml Bounce: 2024-08-22_1200_X1SUSBS_M1M2_Bounce_V_0p01to40Hz.xml Initial Measurement: These values were found by taking a High BW Transfer Function using a noise injection into M1 Vertical in the 2Hz range in the neighborhood of the model values, reading at all BOSEMs in the M2 stage. (19-20Hz for Bounce and 31-33Hz for Roll). We then found the most coherent peak in that region to be our measured mode. Mechanical Mode Confirmation: After this, we ran an ASD and injected a sine wave at the found frequencies one-by-one, ringing up our modes for 5 averages before stopping the injection. We then watched the ASD and confirmed that given the number of averages it took to percieve a gradual ring-down at those frequencies (over 20 averages of for each at 0.02BW assuming a Q-Factor of ~1000, which is conservative), that the readout was indeed mechanical, and that these were indeed our Bounce and Roll modes. Note: While the screenshots may say M3, this is simply because of our set-up being hooked up to the M3 stage electronically. These results were read from the M2 BOSEMs on the PUM of the BBSS. This cabling discrepancy has since been fixed. SUS ","{'term': 'X1 SUS', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: ibrahim.abouelfettouh@ligo.org

Report ID: 79743

Ibrahim A, Jeff K
On 8/22, Jeff K and I ran some measurements of our assembled BBSS and determined the Bounce and Roll modes to be:
I have linked this alog to the SWG Logbook in the case these results are needed for BRD development for the BBSS.
Screenshots of these peaks and the excitation spectra are attached and the Data can be found on the X1 (Test Stand) Network: at /ligo/svncommon/SusSVN/sus/trunk/BBSS/X1/BS/Common/Data/ under names:

These values were found by taking a High BW Transfer Function using a noise injection into M1 Vertical in the 2Hz range in the neighborhood of the model values, reading at all BOSEMs in the M2 stage. (19-20Hz for Bounce and 31-33Hz for Roll). We then found the most coherent peak in that region to be our measured mode.

After this, we ran an ASD and injected a sine wave at the found frequencies one-by-one, ringing up our modes for 5 averages before stopping the injection. We then watched the ASD and confirmed that given the number of averages it took to percieve a gradual ring-down at those frequencies (over 20 averages of for each at 0.02BW assuming a Q-Factor of ~1000, which is conservative), that the readout was indeed mechanical, and that these were indeed our Bounce and Roll modes.

Note: While the screenshots may say M3, this is simply because of our set-up being hooked up to the M3 stage electronically. These results were read from the M2 BOSEMs on the PUM of the BBSS. This cabling discrepancy has since been fixed.

Oberling, R. Short The FSS RefCav TPD had been trending down again, and Ryan did not get enough improvement from a remote alignment tweak last week . So today we went into the enclosure to do an on-table alignment of the FSS RefCav beam path. As usual, we began with a power budget: FSS In: 282.9 mW AOM In: 283.2 mW AOM Out, SP: 174.4 mW SP Diffraction Efficiency: 61.6% AOM Out, DP: 122.8 mW DP Diffraction Efficiency: 70.4% EOM Out: 121.4 mW No, we're not getting magic amplification between the FSS In and AOM In power measurements; that kind of small discrepancy is normal with the small stick power meter head we use for this alignment (they are also very AOI dependent, so it's entirely possible we had the head better aligned to the beam for the AOM In measurement). Immediately we see the single-pass diffraction efficiency is lower than it normally is (generally hangs out in the lower 70% range these days), so we began by adjusting the AOM alignment to improve it. This also means we have to then adjust M21 to improve the double-pass diffraction efficiency. After the adjustments we had: AOM Out, SP: 199.4 mW SP Diffraction Efficiency: 70.4% AOM Out, DP: 143.3 mW DP Diffraction Efficiency: 71.9% This is the lowest we've seen the diffraction efficiencies of this AOM, and suggests maybe it's time to swap the AOM for a new one (pretty sure this is the same AOM installed with the PSL in 2012, would have to go back through the alog to see if it's been swapped since install). As usual, we had to do some small tweaks to the FSS EOM (provides the 21.5 MHz PDH sidebands for RefCav locking), and had to tweak the beam alignment into the RefCav using the input iris. Once done, the RefCav locked without issue and our picomotor mounts were used to maximize the RefCav TPD; we began with a TPD of 0.57 V and ended with a TPD of 0.82 V . We've had it higher in the past, but we have less power out of the PMC than usual (due to our slowly increasing PMC Refl that we have yet to figure out the cause of), and less power out of the PMC means less power available for the FSS RefCav which means lower maximum RefCav TPD. To end we realigned the beam onto the RefCav RFPD and took a visibility measurement: Unlocked: 1.162 V Locked: 0.221 V Visibility: 81.0% This finished the FSS RefCav tune-up, so we left the enclosure. We left the ISS OFF while the enclosure returns to thermal equilibrium; it will be turned back ON once that equilibrium is reached, and Ryan will do a rotation stage calibration. This closes LHO WP 12057 .","{'term': 'H1 PSL', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

No, we're not getting magic amplification between the FSS In and AOM In power measurements; that kind of small discrepancy is normal with the small stick power meter head we use for this alignment (they are also very AOI dependent, so it's entirely possible we had the head better aligned to the beam for the AOM In measurement).  Immediately we see the single-pass diffraction efficiency is lower than it normally is (generally hangs out in the lower 70% range these days), so we began by adjusting the AOM alignment to improve it.  This also means we have to then adjust M21 to improve the double-pass diffraction efficiency.  After the adjustments we had:

This is the lowest we've seen the diffraction efficiencies of this AOM, and suggests maybe it's time to swap the AOM for a new one (pretty sure this is the same AOM installed with the PSL in 2012, would have to go back through the alog to see if it's been swapped since install).  As usual, we had to do some small tweaks to the FSS EOM (provides the 21.5 MHz PDH sidebands for RefCav locking), and had to tweak the beam alignment into the RefCav using the input iris.  Once done, the RefCav locked without issue and our picomotor mounts were used to maximize the RefCav TPD; we began with a TPD of 0.57 V and ended with a TPD of 0.82 V.  We've had it higher in the past, but we have less power out of the PMC than usual (due to our slowly increasing PMC Refl that we have yet to figure out the cause of), and less power out of the PMC means less power available for the FSS RefCav which means lower maximum RefCav TPD.  To end we realigned the beam onto the RefCav RFPD and took a visibility measurement:

Author: david.barker@ligo.org

Report ID: 79735

WP12061 Upgrade RCG h1susex, remove LIGO-DAC delays
h1susex RCG was upgraded to a custom 5.3.0 specifically for the IOP to remove a delay in the new LIGO 28AO32 DAC. We compliled all of the user models with this RCG as well.

Our first restart was a simple model restart, but we got Dolphin errors. So our second restart was to fence h1susex from the Dolphin fabric and power cycle h1susex via IPMI. After this the models started with no issues.
The locklossalert system code was modified to permit an alert window which spans over midnight, needed for the new owl shift hours.

Note that the business/every day filter is applied after the minute-in-day filter, so a window starting Friday evening and extending into Saturday morning will cut off at midnight if business days only is selected.
For everyone subscribed to Guardian alerts, if for any reason the Guardian EPICS record cannot be read (node down, h1guardian1 down) the alert will now default to SEND.
h1guardian1 was rebooted at 08:21 PDT. All nodes except TEST came back automatically. TJ worked on TEST and got it going.

Jonathan removed two test switches from the MSR racks which are no longer needed.

",79735,david.barker@ligo.org

Quiet evening with nothing to report. Feedforward measurements were run, and I also just tuned squeezing up. Little comparison on the damping for new PI over the past 5 days ( ndscope ) Since starting back up last week, we have been seeing a new PI ( 79665 ), and it had caused a few locklosses. On Friday afternoon (08/24 ~00:00UTC - crosshairs on ndscope) it was decided that the easiest way to try and control it for now would be to change our input power from 60W to 61W. This, along with some changes to the damping gain, has helped keep it under control. The changes to damping (I'm not sure what was done besides raising the damping gain) also means that they get caught and damped quickly. TITLE: 08/27 Eve Shift: 2300-0800 UTC (1600-0100 PST), all times posted in UTC
SHIFT SUMMARY: Observing and have been Locked for 5.5 hours. Quiet evening with nothing to report. Feedforward measurements were run, and I also just tuned squeezing up.
Little comparison on the damping for new PI over the past 5 days (ndscope)

Since starting back up last week, we have been seeing a new PI (79665), and it had caused a few locklosses. On Friday afternoon (08/24 ~00:00UTC - crosshairs on ndscope) it was decided that the easiest way to try and control it for now would be to change our input power from 60W to 61W. This, along with some changes to the damping gain, has helped keep it under control. Comparing the PI's behavior to the length of our lock stretches, we only see the ringups during the first 1.5-2 hours of each lock, so once we're thermalized past a certain point, they stop happening. The changes to damping (I'm not sure what was done besides raising the damping gain) also means that they get caught and damped quickly.
04:27 Dropped Observing to take FF measurements
04:46 Feedforward measurements done, running SQZ alignment

1176,59,H1 ISC - OMC Locking with Higher DARM Offset,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79721,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Mon, 26 Aug 2024 14:31:16 -0700","Before the vent, we had lowered the DARM offset used at the end of the DARM_OFFSET state for locking the OMC since we had seen the PRG fall off and cause a lockloss with the nominal offset of 9e-05 (see alog79082 for details). When locking this afternoon, I raised the offset from 6e-05 back to 9e-05 after running through DARM_OFFSET, and seeing that the PRG didn't plummet and cause a lockloss, we continued locking. The OMC locked on the first try, something that hasn't been the case recently, so having more carrier light there seems to help. I compared OMC scans from this lock against the last lock, which used the lower DARM offset; attachment 1 shows the scan with the higher offset and attachment 2 with the lower offset. According to the OMC-DCPD_SUM channel, we get ~10mW more carrier light on the OMC when locking with this higher DARM offset. I've put this DARM offset of 9e-05 back into ISC_LOCK and loaded it. We can watch over the next couple of lock acquisitions to see if the problem wth the PRG dropping off resurfaces. ","{'term': 'H1 ISC', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: ryan.short@ligo.org

Report ID: 79721

Before the vent, we had lowered the DARM offset used at the end of the DARM_OFFSET state for locking the OMC since we had seen the PRG fall off and cause a lockloss with the nominal offset of 9e-05 (see alog79082 for details). When locking this afternoon, I raised the offset from 6e-05 back to 9e-05 after running through DARM_OFFSET, and seeing that the PRG didn't plummet and cause a lockloss, we continued locking. The OMC locked on the first try, something that hasn't been the case recently, so having more carrier light there seems to help. I compared OMC scans from this lock against the last lock, which used the lower DARM offset; attachment 1 shows the scan with the higher offset and attachment 2 with the lower offset. According to the OMC-DCPD_SUM channel, we get ~10mW more carrier light on the OMC when locking with this higher DARM offset.
I've put this DARM offset of 9e-05 back into ISC_LOCK and loaded it. We can watch over the next couple of lock acquisitions to see if the problem wth the PRG dropping off resurfaces.

Author: david.barker@ligo.org

Report ID: 79708

TJ, Jonathan, EJ, Dave:
Around 01:30 this morning we had a Dolphin crash of all the frontends at EY (h1susey, h1seiey, h1iscey). h1susauxey is not on the Dolphin network as was not impacted.
We could not ping these machines, but were able to get some diagnostics from their IPMI management ports.
At 07:57 we powered down h1[sus,sei,isc]ey for about a minute and then powered them back on.
We checked the IX Dolphin switch at EY was responsive on the network.

All the systems came back with no issues. SWWD and model WDs were cleared. TJ is recovering H1.

",79708,david.barker@ligo.org

1189,72,LHO General - Comment to Sat DAY Ops Summary,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79707,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Mon, 26 Aug 2024 08:17:37 -0700","Looking into why the input power didn't come back down after a lockloss at ADS_TO_CAMERAS, seems that the proper decorators that check for a lockloss are missing from the run method (but are there in main). This means that while ISC_LOCK was waiting for the camera servos to turn on, it didn't notice that the IFO lost lock, and therefore didn't run through the LOCKLOSS or DOWN states which would reset the input power. I've added the decorators to the run method of ADS_TO_CAMEARS so this shouldn't happen again. ISC, OpsInfo","{'term': 'LHO General', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: ryan.short@ligo.org

Report ID: 79707

Looking into why the input power didn't come back down after a lockloss at ADS_TO_CAMERAS, seems that the proper decorators that check for a lockloss are missing from the run method (but are there in main). This means that while ISC_LOCK was waiting for the camera servos to turn on, it didn't notice that the IFO lost lock, and therefore didn't run through the LOCKLOSS or DOWN states which would reset the input power.
I've added the decorators to the run method of ADS_TO_CAMEARS so this shouldn't happen again.

Author: corey.gray@ligo.org

Report ID: 79683

TITLE: 08/24 Day Shift: 1430-2330 UTC (0730-1630 PST), all times posted in UTC

Have had the BS camera die on us a couple times in the last 24hrs (this requires contacting Dave to restart the camera's computer--atleast until this camera can be moved to another computer), and so the beginning of the shift was restoring this and also figuring out why H1 had a lockloss, BUT did not drop the Input Power down from 61W to 2W.
After the camera issue was fixed, ran an alignment with no issues, and then took H1 all the back to NLN also with no issues.
Then completed taking Calibration measurements after 1.5hrs and 3hrs.  Oli also ran LSC Feedforward measurements......
Then there was ANOTHER BS Camera Computer Crash!  Dave brought us back fast.

column2: • Arrived to see that H1 was stuck at ADS TO CAMERAS, BUT had had a lockloss.  ALSO: Input Power did not change after the lockloss---so, 61W was being dumped to MC REFL!  Mystery as to why this happened.  I took H1 DOWN and this took care of the High Power onto MC REFL.

column3: • x+y green arms were way out and needed INCREASE FLASHES

column2: • 1635 Noise hunting in Mechanical Room off and on today (robert)

• 1643-1728 Locking H1 & then getting stuck at ADS TO CAMERAS (same as last night)---Noticed that the CAMERA SERVO had stalled and noted issues with CAM1 Pit & Yaw.  Posted this onto LIGO Chat and Ryan Short mentioned it's probably due to the BS' camera.  Sure enough it had died!
• 1800-1807 Contacting Dave to restart the BS camera
• Save & Loaded LASER_PWR.py  (It had already been edited for the change to 61W.)
• 1946-2015 Ran Calibration after H1 was locked for 90min.
• 2042 H1 back to OBSERVING (1st time since July12th!)
<li>2113-2301 Out of Observing:  Running Thermalized Calibration + LSC Feedforward measurements

column3: • Since the BS Camera happen to die during Oli's last LSC FF measurement for PRCL, they ran it again.

column2: • 2226 - 2243 BS Camera was down again!  (Dave brought it back for us pretty fast.)

OK, here's a rough timeline for last night (used the handy "" guardctrl log "" command line command which Camilla was able to help me find; I also attached the guardtrl log for all notes for the minute around the lockloss): 537utc (1037pmlocal): ISC_LOCK at ADS TO CAMERAS 0718 Verbal Alarms: ""H1 Assistance Required"" Not really sure what this was about.... Author: marc.lormand@ligo.org

Report ID: 72894

There were a couple of issues while recovering from the earthquake.

First, during the first lock attempt the ICSEX, SUSEX, and SEIEX frontends went down. Huyen was still here and checked the SEI and ISC at the EX. We ran the diagnostics on each frontend and a restart was recommended for each system. So, Huyen restarted SEIEX and then SUSEX and I restarted ISCEX. The restarts were one at a time and were all successful.
I did have to steer the spot on ETMX for the ALSX to lock, the Guardian was giving that ALS user code error before the spot was aligned.
At that point, the IFO proceeded to lock and run through the Guardian with no problems until it reached LOW NOISE.
There were some SDFs differences that I had to clear to go to OBSERVE, all in EX no doubt due to the restarts.
I took screen shots and accepted the differences but I wasn't very sure about these SDFs so an expert should look this over!

1218,101,L1 PEM - ~7 Hz Harmonics and Higher Frequency Shelves found during End Station Shaker Tests,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72893,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Wed, 28 Aug 2024 18:08:04 -0500","Anamaria, TJ We ran some mechanical sweeps with the shaker at 1 to 10 Hz at both EX and EY. We found that at both end stations, the mechanical shaking produces fringing at multiples of ~7 Hz in DARM . Once we found the fringing, we did additional shaking tests to try and find the exact frequency that produces the maximum fringing. At EX that frequency is ~7.185 Hz. At EY that frequency is ~7.45 Hz. In addition to the fringing, we also found that shaking at these frequencies created some higher frequency shelves (100-400 Hz depending on the amplitude of the shaking). The shelves were more pronounced at EX than EY where they were barely peeking out above DARM but still perceptible. Modeling both the shelves and the harmonics, it seems like they are from different coupling sources. 7 times more motion is required to produce the shelves than the harmonics and the selves seems like there is less light amplitude. The motion to produce the harmonics seems consistent with what we drove with the shaker but the shelves is 7 times more. We tried shaking at the manifold and the spool to try and triangulate the location of the coupling but our accelerometers saw too similar shaking at both locations. We believe that the ~7 Hz is a structural resonance of the beamtube near this location The ~7 Hz peak that is there in the accelerometers varies over time in amplitude but not frequency. More information can be found at the presentation on G2401727 . PEM Non-image files attached to this report EndStationScattering.pdf ","{'term': 'L1 PEM', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: timothy.ohanlon@ligo.org

Report ID: 72893

Anamaria, TJ

We ran some mechanical sweeps with the shaker at 1 to 10 Hz at both EX and EY. We found that at both end stations, the mechanical shaking produces fringing at multiples of ~7 Hz in DARM. Once we found the fringing, we did additional shaking tests to try and find the exact frequency that produces the maximum fringing. At EX that frequency is ~7.185 Hz. At EY that frequency is ~7.45 Hz. In addition to the fringing, we also found that shaking at these frequencies created some higher frequency shelves (100-400 Hz depending on the amplitude of the shaking). The shelves were more pronounced at EX than EY where they were barely peeking out above DARM but still perceptible.

Modeling both the shelves and the harmonics, it seems like they are from different coupling sources. 7 times more motion is required to produce the shelves than the harmonics and the selves seems like there is less light amplitude. The motion to produce the harmonics seems consistent with what we drove with the shaker but the shelves is 7 times more.

We tried shaking at the manifold and the spool to try and triangulate the location of the coupling but our accelerometers saw too similar shaking at both locations. We believe that the ~7 Hz is a structural resonance of the beamtube near this location The ~7 Hz peak that is there in the accelerometers varies over time in amplitude but not frequency. More information can be found at the presentation on G2401727.

Author: marc.lormand@ligo.org

Report ID: 72890

Author: joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org

Report ID: 72888

[Louis D, Joe B]

It was pointed out to me by Valera that the calibration reported koptical gain, supposedly scaled by the inverse of the square root of the power increases, was not matching the actual optical gain.  Louis also pointed out that the digital gains between the DCPD read in and the DARM filter bank were not as stable as they should be.  This can be traced back to some issues in my PSL guardian code that handles the power up steps.

In any case, we can take the excess digital gain changes (beyond the 1/sqrt(power) scaling), out and plot a more approriate ""Kappa C"", which is what the 1st attachment shows, relative to the IM4 TRANS reported power.
In summary, while kappa C looks like it changed by -2% to +5%, once the excessive digital gains are divided out, the changes between various power levels is only +/-2%.

1229,112,L1 PEM - DARM noise projection of PSL accelerometers using long-term coherence (STAMP-PEM),https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72880,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Wed, 28 Aug 2024 01:33:37 -0500","One of the new additions in the summary pages is the STAMP-PEM results (for example see link ) that show the coherence between DARM and various control and environmental channels averaged over a day. In that we see a reasonable coherence between PSL accelerometers and DARM at high frequencies (~300 Hz - 1500 Hz) ( link ). The first two plots show such coherence calculated for a couple PSL accelerometers using 9 hr data from Aug 20, 2024. The red dotted line is the expected coherence assuming two random time-series. We see higher than expected coherence in broader frequency bands especially at high frequencies. One can use this data to make ambient noise projection as we do with the PEM injections. The third figure shows this projection for differnet PSL ACC channels for frequencies where the cohrence is greater than 100 times the expected cohrence (assuming random data). The fourth figure shows the projection using frequency points where coherence only greater than 10 times the background coherence (when the coherence is lower the estiamates have more uncertainities). These results somehwhat agrees with the PEM injection, see O3b results . There are some differences, for example the peaks around ~500 Hz and ~1200 Hz not that strong from the PEM injections. However those results were using O3b PEM injections, maybe with O4a injections some of these differences might go away (which are not available at these frequencies yet). Author: shivaraj.kandhasamy@ligo.org

Report ID: 72880

One of the new additions in the summary pages is the STAMP-PEM results (for example see link) that show the coherence between DARM and various control and environmental channels averaged over a day. In that we see a reasonable coherence between PSL accelerometers and DARM at high frequencies (~300 Hz - 1500 Hz) (link). The first two plots show such coherence calculated for a couple PSL accelerometers using 9 hr data from Aug 20, 2024. The red dotted line is the expected coherence assuming two random time-series. We see higher than expected coherence in broader frequency bands especially at high frequencies.

One can use this data to make ambient noise projection as we do with the PEM injections. The third figure shows this projection for differnet PSL ACC channels for frequencies where the cohrence is greater than 100 times the expected cohrence (assuming random data).  The fourth figure shows the projection using frequency points where coherence only greater than 10 times the background coherence (when the coherence is lower the estiamates have more uncertainities). These results somehwhat agrees with the PEM injection, see O3b results. There are some differences, for example the peaks around ~500 Hz and ~1200 Hz not that strong from the PEM injections. However those results were using O3b PEM injections, maybe with O4a injections some of these differences might go away (which are not available at these frequencies yet).

1233,116,L1 PEM - Noise analysis of the UPS at EX,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72877,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Tue, 27 Aug 2024 19:14:11 -0500","Tabata, Anamaria We verified the changes after the UPS was put on at EX ( alog 71932 ). The conclusions regarding changes in the spectra of some magnetometers and VMONs are very similar at EX and EY; however, regarding the number of glitches, the effects at EX auxiliary channels were slightly worse. Since there is no significant number of 60Hz glitches in DARM, it is not obvious to state whether we are better or worse. However, we can say that with the UPS, 60Hz glitches still do not significantly affect DARM. Information about the UPS at EY can be found in the alog 69881 , and here are the conclusions for EX: A brief analysis of the spectra: In general, the spectra shapes are worse for all mains monitoring and magnetometer channels after the UPS event ( image 1 ); The amplitude of the lines in VMONs and temporary channels is generally lower, except for the 60Hz harmonics at EX_ADC_04_11 (current clamp on rack grounding); ( image 2 ) It seems that the 60Hz heights (purple dots) from the normalized average power are higher after the UPS ( image 3 ); the 120 Hz and 180 Hz levels are similar. We checked and found no ESD bias sign flip or laser power change during this period; Glitches: All mainsmon channels showed a reduction in the number of glitches after UPS ( image 4 - the red dashed vertical line delineates the period before and after the UPS); The MAG_SUSRACK_X channel appears to have more glitches after the UPS ( image 4 ); The MAG_SUSRACK_Y channel has experienced a slight increase in glitches after the UPS ( image 4 ); The MAG_SUSRACK_Z channel is inconclusive since the number of glitches increased prior to the UPS ( image 4 ); The VMONs oscillate but generally seem to be somewhat worse as well ( image5 ); More details can be seen it these slides . Detchar ","{'term': 'L1 PEM', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: tabata.ferreira@ligo.org

Report ID: 72877

Tabata, Anamaria

We verified the changes after the UPS was put on at EX (alog 71932). The conclusions regarding changes in the spectra of some magnetometers and VMONs are very similar at EX and EY; however, regarding the number of glitches, the effects at EX auxiliary channels were slightly worse. Since there is no significant number of 60Hz glitches in DARM, it is not obvious to state whether we are better or worse. However, we can say that with the UPS, 60Hz glitches still do not significantly affect DARM.
Information about the UPS at EY can be found in the alog 69881, and here are the conclusions for EX:

column2: • In general, the spectra shapes are worse for all mains monitoring and magnetometer channels after the UPS event (image 1);
• The amplitude of the lines in VMONs and temporary channels is generally lower, except for the 60Hz harmonics at EX_ADC_04_11 (current clamp on rack grounding); (image 2)

• It seems that the 60Hz heights (purple dots) from the normalized average power are higher after the UPS (image 3); the 120 Hz and 180 Hz levels are similar. We checked and found no ESD bias sign flip or laser power change during this period;
• All mainsmon channels showed a reduction in the number of glitches after UPS (image 4 - the red dashed vertical line delineates the period before and after the UPS);
• The MAG_SUSRACK_X channel appears to have more glitches after the UPS (image 4);
• The MAG_SUSRACK_Y channel has experienced a slight increase in glitches after the UPS (image 4);
• The MAG_SUSRACK_Z channel is inconclusive since the number of glitches increased prior to the UPS (image 4);
• The VMONs oscillate but generally seem to be somewhat worse as well (image5);

column1: More details can be seen it these slides.

Y-arm vacuum bake status temps ~ 145C, pressure @ 1.17e-6 torr. Note: the bake out and spinning turbo will remain active for another week.

Author: joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org

Report ID: 72867

[Vlad B, Joe B, Michael L, Josh C]

Vlad and I began by checking our transmitter box references.  We have two manual flipper mirrors that reflect the beams to back of the box as local pointing reference.  Unfortunately, they were misaligned, so we spent the beginning of maintenance re-aligning them.
I'll be adding a check of those to our bi-monthly pcal efficiency measurements workflow, as well as double checking the X end again next week.

This was followed by dismounting the patch panel of the PCALY system, which was clearly not designed with removal in mind.  We added a power and BNC feedthrough in the EE lab, and reattached the patch panel, but we had mis-judged the edge of the patch panel overlap by a few mm, and currently the top of the power connector is held in place by the black wall of the transmitter box.  So less than ideally, the power for the Thor Labs PD100A is held in by one screw, although securely at the moment.  When we have more time on another maintenance day, we need to fix this, but for now, it is possible to go laser safe.

During the process of disconnecting everything, we discovered one BNC between the optical follower servo board and the AOM RF driver modulation input was loose.  This is directly in the feedback for the optical follower servo and could explain the poor behavior we have been seeing.  So after connecting everything again, and double checking all connections, we decided to hold off doing the RF driver swap (partly because we ran out of time), and will monitor until we see a glitch or failure mode.

We have put a razor blade beam dump in the path, after the TX and OFS PDs.  So PCALY is still not running on the main interferometer, but we are running typical sized excitations through the AOM to stress test this over the week.  If we see a problem again, we'll immediately pull the chassis and swap the driver as the next step.CAL",72867,joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org

1244,127,L1 General - History of the 11.9 Hz comb in DARM,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72866,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Tue, 27 Aug 2024 13:50:23 -0500","This post summarizes some features of the 11.9 Hz comb's history over O4 so far. The intent is to help evaluate the impact of 72765 and compare to previous 11.9 Hz comb studies. The comb decreased in strength mid O4a, and was fairly weak in the latter part of O4a. However, it increased again between O4a and O4b. There have been two examples of relatively short (1-2 weeks) exceptionally strong time periods followed by a sharp drop-off. Of these: one drop seems to align with an ETMX bias sign change on Sept 12, 2023 ( 67581 ). one drop seems to align with the recent EX Beckhoff relocation on Aug 20, 2024 ( 72765 ). There are other, less drastic but still distinct changes over both O4a and O4b (see plots). Below, I link to a number of interactive plots, because these are useful for seeing the detailed behavior/structure of the comb. I have also attached static images of the same plots, in case the interactive versions are accidentally deleted at a later time. History of the comb Tracking the first two (strongest) peaks at 11.9 and 35.7 Hz Tracking all comb peaks in the 10-100 Hz range How to read the history plots: the small colorful dots show the height of peak of the comb (specifically, odd harmonics of 11.9046967 Hz) in the specified frequency range. You can use the color bar and the mouseover text to get the specific frequency information. The square black dots show the median height of all the peaks considered, to provide a general measurement of the comb height. Their hover text gives the date, and the number of 1800s SFTs averaged to create the spectrum from which that data point is drawn. The small blue lines show the 1st and 99th percentile of all the data in the band, and are mainly a visual check for unreliable data (generally due to low SFT counts, and indicated by a wide separation of the small blue lines); they are less important for interpreting the plot. The ""height"" here is normalized average power, as computed with Fscans. That is, the height is relative to the noise floor in the spectral region nearby the peak. For more detail, the representative plots below show a daily average PSD, also from Fscans, but which is not normalized. Representative daily spectra & comparisons Early O4a, strong, 20230625 Late O4a, weak, 20231226 Early O4b, strong, 20240408 Recent, very strong, 20240818 Recent, weak, 20240825 Comparison of early O4b against late O4a Comparison of recent spectra before and after the sharp drop 8/20-8/21 The static plots attached below are in the same order as these links. 1255,138,Working Groups DetChar - DQ Shift report for the week from 2024-08-12 to 2024-08-18,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72854,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Mon, 26 Aug 2024 21:16:34 -0500","Below is the summary of the DQ shift for the week from 2024-08-12 to 2024-08-18 During this week, the BNS range was between ~155 - 178 Mpc. Usually, the range variations were seen with the timescales of 12 hours or so. But, sometimes, we also see smaller BNS range variations of half-hour/hour time scales. On Aug 18, 2024, due to PCALY failure, the range dropped to ~100 Mpc for an hour or so. We observe excess noise in the 20 - 80 Hz band during the times of low BNS range ( figure1 ). We see excess low SNR (~ < 5) omicron triggers in the 50- 100 Hz band during the times of low BNS range ( figure 2 ). We see a bit of disjoint between the frequency regions in the strain noise spectrogram and the omicron triggers. During most of the days in this week, we see that the rate of the SNR triggers (SNR > 5) starts low at the beginning of the lock and steadily increases (by a factor of 2 or 3) in an hour or two and then stays there or comes down a little after few hours ( figure 3 ). This is especially true when there is a long gap between the locks. We do not see strong features in the PEM channels (accelerometers and mics) that correlate with the noise in DARM. We also do not see any consistent channels showing up in LASSO tracking the slow variations in range. In Hveto, the following channels consistently appear as winners of the first few rounds. However, their efficiency in removing the glitches is not high. L1:ASC-Y_TR_B_NSUM_OUT_DQ, L1:LSC-REFL_A_LF_OUT_DQ Also, on the day of the power glitch (Aug 15, 2024), L1:PEM-CS_MAG_LVEA_VERTEX_X_DQ shows up as one of the winners vetoing glitches just before the lockloss (due to the power glitch). In Fscan, we don't see any obvious new set of lines during this week. We still see the wandering line around 580 Hz and other associated lines ( a-log 70869 ) The full DQ shift report with day-by-day details is available at https://wiki.ligo.org/DetChar/DataQuality/DQShiftLLO20240812 Detchar ","{'term': 'Working Groups DetChar', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: vladimir.bossilkov@ligo.org

Report ID: 72836

w/ JoeB
Our PcalY is intermittently failing, in a similar fashion to: [72799], though this time going out for as much as 5 minutes, with many later smaller dropouts.
We have once again transitioned from PcalY to PcalX similar to conversation in [72724]. This time we transitioned more smoothly via work done in [72788].

We had to linger in IFO ready state with the intent bit off in order for downstream calibration line subtraction to catch up. We waited a little while to let the subtraction return to nominal operation before flipping the intent bit, and returning to observing.
HIGH_FREQ_LINES guardian was placed into IDLE operation manually as I haven't had time to re-think and re-write a better state of operation for it handling pcal transitions.
The extra PcalY sensor placed by JoeB and TJ [72774] seems to reveal that the laser is working fine.

I only show the temporary accelerometer at the shaker location and the accelerometer at the manifold (right underneath the cryobaffle location). Author: anamaria.effler@ligo.org

Report ID: 72824

TJ, Anamaria

As part of scatter investigations trying to localize the end station scatter coupling, we also performed sweeps. Here I show the 10 to 30 Hz sweeps, performed with a shaker connected at the cryo pump spool piece (right before second GV from ETM). I only show the temporary accelerometer at the shaker location and the accelerometer at the manifold (right underneath the cryobaffle location). The spectrograms are normalized, and the range is up to 100, so where there is yellow the coupling is not so worrisome because we have to inject at least 100 above ambient to see signal in DARM. However, there are frequencies where we're not injecting so much (one example each is showcased by the vertical magenta lines).

Interestingly, that particular section of the beam tube near the cryo pump is moving a lot more than others, even reaching 10 um/s at ~21 Hz. This is true at both ends, and is confirmed by other nearby accelerometers. We don't know why, it could be due to the cryo pump. But if we have scattered light there (which we know we do from photos), it's not ideal.

1286,169,L1 PEM - End station ISCTEX and ISCTEY don't show scatter coupling,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72823,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Fri, 23 Aug 2024 17:03:54 -0500","TJ, Anamaria In the past few weeks we've been investigating end station scatter, and one of the checks is if there's any backscatter from the table. We added a temporary accelerometer to the tables, and a small shaker on the cross-leg. Looking at the spectra there seem to be some vibration peaks around 10 and 15, so we shook those in particular. If there were light to be scattered, it would show up in DARM and we would investigate further but we saw no DARM response. Attached are two examples, one for EX and one for EY. In the EX test there's some 21 Hz noise, but it is unrelated (did not coincide with our turn on/off of our injection). All tests are in dtt files in /data/PEM/O4/EXVibration/ (or EY). Author: anamaria.effler@ligo.org

Report ID: 72823

TJ, Anamaria

In the past few weeks we've been investigating end station scatter, and one of the checks is if there's any backscatter from the table. We added a temporary accelerometer to the tables, and a small shaker on the cross-leg. Looking at the spectra there seem to be some vibration peaks around 10 and 15, so we shook those in particular. If there were light to be scattered, it would show up in DARM and we would investigate further but we saw no DARM response.
Attached are two examples, one for EX and one for EY. In the EX test there's some 21 Hz noise, but it is unrelated (did not coincide with our turn on/off of our injection).
All tests are in dtt files in /data/PEM/O4/EXVibration/ (or EY).

Author: anamaria.effler@ligo.org

Report ID: 72817

This noise seems to come and go over a period of 12 hrs, and it was plaguing us a lot at 71W. We have been at 56W for a week now, but we can still see this variation, possibly to a smaller extent. Some other info in this report and its comments.
The first attachment shows a few days of this variation, in range and darm bands that are affected.

Second attachment: We did one test of changing the EX VEA temperature last week, and that seemed to quickly affect the range, but we lost lock an hour after. We retained that set point for a week (67F), but the 12 hr range oscillation continued. So this week we did another few steps between the two temperatures, and while they seem to affect the range, it's not in the same way as before. However, the correlation is there. It almost seems like a transient behavior, ie something happens when we change the temperature, but when it's back to normal operation, the exact setpoint doesn't affect things?

Third attachment: We then also did the same temperature test at EY, but only one step to 67F and back to 68F, the range seemed unaffected. It was not constant during the test, but there are no additional changes/kinks at the times of the EY temp changes (unlike EX). This makes EY less likely to be the culprit.

Fourth attachment: We did a 21 Hz injection at EX, seeing both a peak and a higher frequency shelf, and then changed the beam spot position on ETMX to see if we could reduce it. The nominal position is -3mm, we moved by another 8mm and it seemed to affect the noise. We did not go further as we started to lose optical gain. Then we tried to find an intermediary position where the noise was low, but it was not exactly reproducible... So we moved past our nominal position, to 0 and left it there. We adjusted the A2L gain to compensate. The noise seemed lower than when we started, outside of the injection period. But again it's not reproducible, despite seemingly affecting the noise.

Report ID: 72818

While trying to get data Valera found the readback for a DQ'd channel has been bad for the last 100 days or so because of a bad burt restore it looks like from a reboot or power outage.

I set L1:ASC-Y_TR_ERM_POW_NORM to 1.0 from 0.0, and saved it in SDF, as well updated the l1iscey_safe.snap by hand.  I checked both into SVN.  The channel is now being recorded properly.",72818,joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org

Author: vladimir.bossilkov@ligo.org

Report ID: 72812

w/ Begum, JoeH
We had a pair of SQZ dropouts with presently not clear reason.
The first time SQZ re-locked successfully, but only for a few minutes and lost lock again. The second time the green FC locking would not hold long enough for FC locking to complete.
Begum investigated and corrected the FC alignment to improve green power to allow the FC to lock and hand off ASC control to IR light.
We were back to regular observing ~00:15 CDT, 23 Aug.
